const TEST1_DATA = // Mock Test 1
[
  {num:1,text:"Feature Integration Theory by Anne Treisman suggests that attention is required for:",A:"Detecting basic features",B:"Binding features into objects",C:"Sensory storage",D:"Automatic processing",ans:"B",exp:"Feature Integration Theory, proposed by Anne Treisman, states that basic features like color or shape are processed automatically. However, focused attention is necessary to combine these separate features into a unified object. Without attention, errors like illusory conjunctions can occur in perception."},
  {num:2,text:"When participants report their immediate conscious experiences (e.g., brightness of light or perception of an object), the method used is BEST described as:",A:"Psychoanalysis",B:"Introspection",C:"Catharsis",D:"Conditioning",ans:"B",exp:"Introspection is a method used in early psychology, especially by Wilhelm Wundt, where individuals examine and report their own conscious experiences. It focuses on subjective awareness, such as sensations and feelings, helping researchers understand the structure of the mind."},
  {num:3,text:"Which neuronal structure is primarily responsible for transmitting action potentials away from the soma?",A:"Dendrites",B:"Synapse",C:"Axon",D:"Myelin sheath",ans:"C",exp:"The axon is the long projection of a neuron that carries electrical impulses, known as action potentials, away from the soma or cell body. It ensures communication with other neurons, muscles, or glands, enabling efficient transmission of information across the nervous system."},
  {num:4,text:"A researcher selects intact groups (e.g., entire classes) rather than individuals to represent different population segments. The selection is random at the group level but not within groups. This sampling technique is BEST described as:",A:"Simple random sampling",B:"Cluster sampling",C:"Opportunity sampling",D:"Haphazard sampling",ans:"B",exp:"Cluster sampling involves dividing a population into groups or clusters and randomly selecting entire clusters for study. It is practical when populations are large or geographically dispersed, though it may introduce more sampling error compared to selecting individuals randomly."},
  {num:5,text:"Which term is conceptually equivalent to the assumption of equal variance across groups in statistical testing?",A:"Heteroscedasticity",B:"Homoscedasticity",C:"Covariance",D:"Leptokurtosis",ans:"B",exp:"Homoscedasticity refers to the assumption that different groups in a dataset have equal variances. This assumption is crucial in many statistical tests, such as ANOVA and regression, as unequal variances can affect the validity and reliability of the results."},
  {num:6,text:"The concept of attribution was first systematically proposed by:",A:"Fritz Heider",B:"Leon Festinger",C:"Albert Bandura",D:"Henri Tajfel",ans:"A",exp:"The concept of attribution was systematically introduced by Fritz Heider. He proposed that individuals naturally seek to explain causes of behavior, either attributing them to internal dispositions or external situations. This foundational idea later influenced social psychology theories on perception and judgment."},
  {num:7,text:"A person unconsciously attributes unacceptable internal impulses to an external object, often perceiving the object as possessing those same qualities. This process is BEST described as:",A:"Displacement",B:"Cathexis",C:"Projection",D:"Personification",ans:"C",exp:"Projection is a defense mechanism described in psychoanalytic theory by Sigmund Freud. It involves attributing one’s own unacceptable thoughts or feelings to others. This unconscious process helps reduce anxiety by externalizing internal conflicts instead of acknowledging them within oneself."},
  {num:8,text:"Leon Festinger proposed that dissonance occurs when:",A:"Two behaviors are identical",B:"Cognitions are inconsistent",C:"Memory fails",D:"Perception is biased",ans:"B",exp:"According to Leon Festinger, cognitive dissonance arises when a person holds inconsistent beliefs, attitudes, or behaviors. This inconsistency creates psychological discomfort, motivating the individual to reduce dissonance by changing beliefs, attitudes, or actions to restore internal consistency."},
  {num:9,text:"In classical conditioning, when the conditioned stimulus (CS) is presented and continues until the unconditioned stimulus (UCS) begins, this is termed:",A:"Trace conditioning",B:"Delay conditioning",C:"Simultaneous conditioning",D:"Backward conditioning",ans:"B",exp:"Delay conditioning occurs when the conditioned stimulus is presented first and remains present until the unconditioned stimulus appears. This overlap helps establish a strong association between stimuli, making it one of the most effective forms of classical conditioning for learning responses."},
  {num:10,text:"An approach focusing on internal mental operations such as memory, reasoning, and decision-making—rather than observable behavior—is referred to as:",A:"Behavioral orientation",B:"Biological reductionism",C:"Cognitive orientation",D:"Subjectivism",ans:"C",exp:"Cognitive orientation emphasizes studying mental processes like thinking, memory, and decision-making. It contrasts with behaviorism by focusing on internal mechanisms rather than observable actions. This approach has significantly shaped modern psychology, especially in understanding learning, perception, and problem-solving processes."},
  {num:11,text:"Which feature of simple random sampling MOST directly allows statistical generalization to the population?",A:"Freedom of respondent selection",B:"Known probability of selection for each unit",C:"Guaranteed representativeness",D:"Voluntary participation",ans:"B",exp:"Simple random sampling ensures that every individual in a population has a known and equal probability of selection. This feature minimizes bias and allows researchers to make valid statistical generalizations about the entire population based on the sample results."},
  {num:12,text:"Assertion: According to Stanley Milgram study People obey authority even when actions conflict with personal morals. Reason: Authority reduces personal responsibility perception.",A:"Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation",B:"Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation",C:"A is true, R is false",D:"A is false, R is true",ans:"A",exp:"Stanley Milgram demonstrated that individuals often obey authority figures despite moral conflicts. This occurs partly because authority figures diffuse personal responsibility, making individuals feel less accountable for their actions. Thus, the reason correctly explains why obedience to authority is so powerful."},
  {num:13,text:"Following a left temporoparietal stroke, a patient produces fluent but meaningless speech and shows marked impairment in comprehension. The MOST likely diagnosis is:",A:"Broca’s aphasia",B:"Wernicke’s aphasia",C:"Dyslexia",D:"Apraxia",ans:"B",exp:"Carl Wernicke identified this type of aphasia, where speech remains fluent but lacks meaning, and comprehension is severely impaired. It typically results from damage to the left temporoparietal region, specifically Wernicke’s area, which is crucial for language understanding and semantic processing."},
  {num:14,text:"In an experiment, extraneous variables systematically vary along with the independent variable, making causal interpretation ambiguous. This is known as:",A:"Experimenter bias",B:"Confounding",C:"Placebo effect",D:"Demand characteristics",ans:"B",exp:"Confounding occurs when an extraneous variable changes alongside the independent variable, making it unclear which factor actually caused the observed effect. This threatens internal validity, as researchers cannot confidently determine whether results are due to the intended manipulation or the confounding variable."},
  {num:15,text:"Which of the following Eriksonian stages MOST closely overlaps developmentally and functionally with the oral stage described by Sigmund Freud?",A:"Autonomy vs shame",B:"Trust vs mistrust",C:"Initiative vs guilt",D:"Identity vs role confusion",ans:"B",exp:"The oral stage by Sigmund Freud occurs in infancy and focuses on dependency and gratification through oral activities. This aligns with Erik Erikson’s stage of trust vs mistrust, where infants develop trust based on caregiver responsiveness and reliability."},
  {num:16,text:"Edward Thorndike’s multifactor theory lies at one extreme of the debate regarding:",A:"Unitary vs multiple intelligence structure",B:"Emotional vs cognitive processing",C:"Nature vs nurture",D:"Conscious vs unconscious processes",ans:"A",exp:"Edward Thorndike proposed that intelligence consists of many independent elements or abilities. This contrasts with unitary theories like Spearman’s g-factor, placing Thorndike’s view at the multiple-intelligence extreme of the debate about the structure of intelligence."},
  {num:17,text:"Parenting characterized by high warmth, high control, and bidirectional communication is MOST consistent with:",A:"Authoritarian style",B:"Authoritative style",C:"Permissive style",D:"Neglectful style",ans:"B",exp:"The authoritative parenting style, identified by Diana Baumrind, combines warmth with appropriate control and open communication. Parents set clear expectations while encouraging independence, leading to better social, emotional, and cognitive outcomes in children compared to other parenting styles."},
  {num:18,text:"Which of the following is NOT consistent with connectionist models by David Rumelhart & James McClelland?",A:"Parallel processing",B:"Distributed representation",C:"Serial symbolic processing",D:"Learning via weight adjustment",ans:"C",exp:"Connectionist models proposed by David Rumelhart and James McClelland emphasize parallel distributed processing and learning through weight adjustments in neural networks. Serial symbolic processing, characteristic of classical AI models, is inconsistent with connectionist approaches."},
  {num:19,text:"A child who shows minimal social reciprocity, lack of eye contact, and indifference to physical affection is MOST indicative of:",A:"ADHD",B:"Separation anxiety disorder",C:"Autism spectrum disorder",D:"Reactive attachment disorder",ans:"C",exp:"Autism spectrum disorder is characterized by deficits in social communication and interaction, including reduced eye contact, limited emotional reciprocity, and lack of responsiveness to social cues. These symptoms typically appear early in development and affect the child’s ability to form typical social relationships."},
  {num:20,text:"The chi-square goodness-of-fit test is MOST accurately described as:",A:"A comparison between two independent samples",B:"A test comparing observed frequencies to expected frequencies",C:"A parametric alternative to ANOVA",D:"A rank-based non-parametric test",ans:"B",exp:"The chi-square goodness-of-fit test evaluates whether observed frequencies differ significantly from expected frequencies based on a theoretical distribution. It is a non-parametric test commonly used with categorical data to assess how well the data fit a hypothesized model."},
  {num:21,text:"The defining feature of catatonic schizophrenia involves:",A:"Unable to move with Disorganized thought",B:"Motoric immobility or excessive purposeless activity",C:"Delusions of persecution",D:"Auditory hallucinations",ans:"B",exp:"Catatonic schizophrenia is primarily marked by disturbances in motor behavior, such as extreme immobility (stupor), rigidity, or excessive, purposeless movement. These motor symptoms distinguish it from other subtypes, which are more dominated by hallucinations, delusions, or disorganized thinking."},
  {num:22,text:"The stage of counseling in which the client gains a clearer understanding of their concerns and begins to develop hope and direction is:",A:"In-depth exploration",B:"Commitment to action",C:"Initial disclosure",D:"None of the above",ans:"A",exp:"In the in-depth exploration stage, clients begin to understand their thoughts, emotions, and problems more clearly. This insight fosters hope and direction, as they start recognizing patterns and underlying issues, preparing them for later stages where concrete actions and changes are implemented."},
  {num:23,text:"A learning method that sequences content into small, structured steps with immediate feedback is BEST described as:",A:"Operant conditioning",B:"Programmed learning",C:"Observational learning",D:"Insight learning",ans:"B",exp:"Programmed learning, influenced by B. F. Skinner, presents information in small steps with immediate feedback. This structured approach reinforces correct responses and promotes active learning, making it effective for mastering new material systematically and efficiently."},
  {num:24,text:"Which of the following is NOT a characteristic of mean?",A:"Affected by extreme scores",B:"Minimizes squared deviations",C:"Sum of deviations equals zero",D:"Best used with ordinal data",ans:"D",exp:"The mean is sensitive to extreme values and minimizes the sum of squared deviations from itself. Additionally, deviations from the mean sum to zero. However, it is not suitable for ordinal data, as such data lack equal intervals, making median a better measure. Q 25 - Match the following : | List I (Disorder) | List II (Description) | | --- | --- | | A. Capgras syndrome | 1. Belief of duplicate self | | B. Cotard’s syndrome | 2. Belief one is dead | | C. Fregoli delusion | 3. Familiar people seen as impostors | | D. Doppelgänger phenomenon | 4. Different people seen as one person in disguise | Codes: A-3, B-1, C-4, D-2 A-3, B-4, C-1, D-2 A-3, B-2, C-4, D-1 A-3, B-1, C-4, D-2 Ans-C Capgras syndrome involves believing familiar individuals are impostors, while Cotard’s syndrome includes nihilistic delusions such as believing one is dead. Fregoli delusion involves misidentifying different people as one disguised person, and the Doppelgänger phenomenon refers to perceiving a duplicate of oneself."},
  {num:26,text:"Which measure is used to compare dispersion across datasets with different units?",A:"Range",B:"Standard deviation",C:"Coefficient of variation",D:"Mean deviation",ans:"C",exp:"The coefficient of variation expresses standard deviation relative to the mean, making it unit-free. This allows meaningful comparison of variability across datasets with different scales or units, unlike standard deviation or range, which are affected by the measurement units of the data."},
  {num:27,text:"A therapist exposes a patient to an intense fear stimulus and prevents escape until anxiety subsides. This technique is BEST termed:",A:"Systematic desensitization",B:"Flooding",C:"Inhibition therapy",D:"Aversion therapy",ans:"B",exp:"Flooding is a behavioral therapy technique where a client is exposed directly to a highly anxiety-provoking stimulus without gradual buildup. The individual remains exposed until the anxiety decreases, helping to extinguish the fear response through prolonged exposure without avoidance."},
  {num:28,text:"Inductive reasoning goes from specific to general. Which is analogous to this process?",A:"Top-down processing",B:"Bottom-up processing",C:"Perceptual constancy",D:"Illusion",ans:"B",exp:"Inductive reasoning involves building general conclusions from specific observations. This is analogous to bottom-up processing, where perception begins with sensory input and builds toward a complete understanding, rather than using prior knowledge as in top-down processing."},
  {num:29,text:"Persistent fabrication of memories without intent to deceive, often seen in chronic alcohol misuse, is characteristic of:",A:"Schizophrenia",B:"Korsakoff’s syndrome",C:"OCD",D:"Bipolar disorder",ans:"B",exp:"Korsakoff’s syndrome, often linked to chronic alcohol misuse and thiamine deficiency, involves severe memory impairment. Patients may confabulate, meaning they unintentionally create false memories to fill gaps, without any intention to deceive, reflecting underlying neurological damage."},
  {num:30,text:"Who developed the concept of Primary Mental Abilities?",A:"Raymond Cattell",B:"Edward Thorndike",C:"Louis Leon Thurstone",D:"J P Guilford",ans:"C",exp:"Louis Leon Thurstone proposed that intelligence consists of several independent abilities, such as verbal comprehension, numerical ability, and spatial visualization. This theory challenged the idea of a single general intelligence factor dominating cognitive performance."},
  {num:31,text:"Which of the following statements MOST challenges the strict hierarchical nature of Abraham Maslow’s theory?",A:"Deficiency motivation is conscious; growth motivation is unconscious",B:"Higher needs emerge only after lower needs are satisfied",C:"Individuals may pursue self-actualization despite unmet basic needs",D:"Motivation is unconscious",ans:"C",exp:"Abraham Maslow proposed that needs are arranged hierarchically, but real-life observations show individuals sometimes pursue higher goals like self-actualization despite lacking basic needs. This challenges the rigid, stepwise progression suggested in the original hierarchy model."},
  {num:32,text:"As sample size approaches infinity, the t-distribution:",A:"Becomes more skewed",B:"Becomes broader than normal",C:"Approaches the normal distribution",D:"Becomes bimodal",ans:"C",exp:"The t-distribution is similar to the normal distribution but has heavier tails for small sample sizes. As the sample size increases, variability decreases and the distribution becomes more symmetric, eventually approximating the normal distribution due to reduced standard error and increased stability of estimates."},
  {num:33,text:"Paradoxical intention is a technique rooted in:",A:"CBT",B:"Existential therapy",C:"Logotherapy",D:"Gestalt therapy",ans:"C",exp:"Paradoxical intention, developed by Viktor Frankl, involves encouraging clients to engage in or exaggerate feared behaviors or thoughts. This reduces anxiety by breaking the cycle of fear and avoidance, helping individuals gain control over symptoms through humor and cognitive distancing."},
  {num:34,text:"Relying on information that comes most easily to mind reflects:",A:"Confirmation bias",B:"Availability heuristic",C:"Representativeness heuristic",D:"Anchoring bias",ans:"B",exp:"The availability heuristic refers to judging the likelihood of events based on how easily examples come to mind. This cognitive shortcut can lead to biased decisions, as more memorable or recent events are often overestimated in importance compared to less salient information."},
  {num:35,text:"Helping behavior without expectation of reward is BEST termed:",A:"Prosocial behavior",B:"Altruism",C:"Obligation",D:"Reciprocity",ans:"B",exp:"Altruism refers to selfless helping behavior performed without any expectation of personal gain or reward. It is a subset of prosocial behavior and is often motivated by empathy, moral values, or concern for others’ well-being rather than external incentives or social obligations"},
  {num:37,text:"In the Richard Atkinson–Richard Shiffrin model, which process explains transfer to long term memory MOST effectively?",A:"Rehearsal",B:"Attention",C:"Encoding depth",D:"Chunking",ans:"A",exp:"The Richard Atkinson and Richard Shiffrin model emphasizes rehearsal as the key mechanism for transferring information from short-term to long-term memory. Repetition strengthens memory traces, increasing the likelihood that information is encoded and retained over time."},
  {num:38,text:"A subject attributes false belief correctly but fails second-order belief tasks. This suggests limitation in:",A:"Theory of Mind acquisition",B:"Executive function",C:"Meta-representation",D:"Language processing",ans:"C",exp:"Second-order belief tasks require understanding what one person thinks about another person’s thoughts. Failure here suggests difficulty in meta-representation, which involves representing representations themselves. This is a higher-order cognitive skill beyond basic theory of mind abilities."},
  {num:39,text:"Cognitive flexibility and set-shifting are BEST assessed using:",A:"Digit span",B:"Bender Gestalt",C:"Wisconsin Card Sorting Test",D:"TAT",ans:"C",exp:"The Wisconsin Card Sorting Test measures cognitive flexibility, particularly the ability to shift strategies in response to changing rules. It is widely used to assess executive functioning and is sensitive to frontal lobe dysfunction."},
  {num:40,text:"A visual display showing the relationship between two continuous variables is called:",A:"Histogram",B:"Scatterplot",C:"Bar graph",D:"Frequency polygon",ans:"B",exp:"A scatterplot is used to represent the relationship between two continuous variables by plotting data points on a graph. It helps in identifying patterns, trends, and correlations, making it a fundamental tool in statistical analysis and research interpretation. 41 Q- Match the following : Stages of Sleep | List I | List II | | --- | --- | | A. NREM Stage 1 | 1. Sleep spindles | | B. NREM Stage 2 | 2. Deep slow-wave sleep | | C. NREM Stage 3 | 3. Hypnagogic imagery | | D. REM sleep | 4. Dreaming & paralysis | Codes: A-1, B-3, C-4, D-2 A-3, B-1, C-2, D-4 A-4, B-3, C-1, D-2 A-2, B-1, C-3, D-4 Ans B NREM Stage 1 involves light sleep with hypnagogic imagery. Stage 2 is marked by sleep spindles and K-complexes. Stage 3 includes deep slow-wave sleep, crucial for restoration. REM sleep is associated with vivid dreaming and muscle paralysis, preventing physical enactment of dreams."},
  {num:42,text:"In expectancy-value theory (Martin Fishbein & Icek Ajzen), behavior is predicted by:",A:"Reinforcement history",B:"Attitude × belief strength",C:"Cognitive load",D:"Schema activation",ans:"B",exp:"The theory by Martin Fishbein and Icek Ajzen proposes that behavior is predicted by attitudes formed through beliefs and their evaluations. The strength of beliefs combined with value determines intention and ultimately guides behavior."},
  {num:43,text:"Helping behavior without expectation of reward is BEST termed:",A:"Prosocial behavior",B:"Altruism",C:"Obligation",D:"Reciprocity",ans:"B",exp:"Altruism refers to helping others purely for their benefit, without expecting any reward or return. It reflects genuine concern for others’ welfare and is often driven by empathy, moral principles, or social values rather than external reinforcement or obligation."},
  {num:44,text:"Match theorists with theories: List I | List II",A:"A-1, B-2, C-3, D-4",B:"A-2, B-1, C-3, D-4",C:"A-1, B-3, C-2, D-4",D:"A-4, B-2, C-3, D-1",ans:"A",exp:"Fritz Heider proposed balance theory, Irving Janis introduced groupthink, Muzafer Sherif explained intergroup conflict, and Robert Zajonc described how repeated exposure increases liking."},
  {num:45,text:"“People with a biological predisposition for difficulty in regulating emotions, combined with an invalidating family environment, develop borderline personality disorder.” This assumption belongs to:",A:"Psychoanalysis - Fraud",B:"Stress theory - Marsha Linehan",C:"Schachter-Singer Theory",D:"Cognitive Appraisal Theory",ans:"B",exp:"Marsha Linehan proposed the biosocial theory, explaining borderline personality disorder as arising from emotional vulnerability combined with an invalidating environment. This interaction leads to poor emotion regulation, impulsivity, and unstable interpersonal relationships."},
  {num:46,text:"According to George Kelly A client interprets events based on unique personal meanings and anticipations rather than objective reality. This reflects:",A:"Locus of control",B:"Personal construct theory",C:"Trait theory",D:"Behaviorism",ans:"B",exp:"George Kelly suggested that individuals interpret the world through personal constructs, which are unique cognitive frameworks. These constructs shape expectations and perceptions, meaning behavior is guided more by subjective interpretations than objective reality."},
  {num:47,text:"Severe, recurrent temper outbursts that are grossly out of proportion to the situation and inconsistent with developmental level are characteristic of:",A:"Major depressive disorder",B:"Dysthymia",C:"Disruptive Mood Dysregulation Disorder",D:"Bipolar disorder",ans:"C",exp:"Disruptive Mood Dysregulation Disorder (DMDD) is characterized by persistent irritability and frequent, intense temper outbursts that are disproportionate to the situation. It is typically diagnosed in children and helps distinguish chronic irritability from episodic mood disorders like bipolar disorder."},
  {num:48,text:"Two individuals with similar traits behave differently under stress due to cognitive interpretation of situations. This BEST supports:",A:"Trait theory",B:"Psychoanalysis",C:"CAPS model",D:"Behaviorism",ans:"C",exp:"The CAPS model by Walter Mischel emphasizes that behavior varies depending on how individuals cognitively interpret situations. It highlights the interaction between personal traits and situational factors in determining behavior."},
  {num:49,text:"Systematic desensitization is based on the principle of:",A:"Cognitive restructuring",B:"Reciprocal inhibition",C:"Challenging irrational thoughts",D:"Insight",ans:"B",exp:"Systematic desensitization, developed by Joseph Wolpe, is based on reciprocal inhibition. This principle states that anxiety and relaxation cannot occur simultaneously, so relaxation techniques are used to gradually countercondition fear responses."},
  {num:50,text:"In Rational-Emotive Behavior Therapy (REBT):",A:"Clients are encouraged to take responsibility for their choices",B:"Clients learn to challenge irrational beliefs",C:"The therapist helps clients identify irrational thoughts directly",D:"To change the clients irrational emotion conflicts into rational behavior",ans:"B",exp:"Albert Ellis developed REBT, which focuses on identifying and challenging irrational beliefs that lead to emotional distress. By restructuring these beliefs into rational ones, clients can change maladaptive emotions and behaviors effectively."},
  {num:51,text:"Providing equal resources and opportunities to all people reflects which ethical principle?",A:"Veracity",B:"Autonomy",C:"Justice",D:"Fidelity",ans:"C",exp:"Justice is an ethical principle emphasizing fairness, equality, and impartiality. It requires that individuals are treated equitably and provided equal access to resources and opportunities, especially in professional practices like psychology, healthcare, and research."},
  {num:52,text:"Match the following: Identify the Disorder List I (Symptom) | List II (Disorder)",A:"Inability to recognize faces | 1. Prosopagnosia",B:"Repetition of others' words | 2. Echolalia",C:"Loss of ability to perform learned movements | 3. Apraxia",D:"Inability to identify objects | 4. Agnosia",ans:"A",exp:"Prosopagnosia involves inability to recognize faces, echolalia is repetition of speech, apraxia refers to difficulty performing learned motor tasks, and agnosia involves inability to recognize objects despite intact sensory function, reflecting specific cortical processing impairments."},
  {num:53,text:"In insight learning, the sudden restructuring of a problem leading to an immediate solution is described as:",A:"Incremental learning",B:"Trial-and-error shift",C:"‘Aha’ experience",D:"Associative chaining",ans:"C",exp:"Insight learning, studied by Wolfgang Köhler, involves a sudden realization of a solution without gradual trial-and-error. This “Aha” experience reflects a reorganization of the problem in the mind, leading to immediate understanding and problem resolution."},
  {num:54,text:"A researcher manipulates one variable while controlling others to observe its effect. This is:",A:"Correlational design",B:"Experimental design",C:"Longitudinal study",D:"Cross-sectional study",ans:"B",exp:"Experimental design involves manipulation of an independent variable while controlling extraneous variables to observe its causal effect on a dependent variable. This method allows researchers to establish cause-and-effect relationships with high internal validity compared to non-experimental designs."},
  {num:55,text:"The median of the following data is: 2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12",A:"6",B:"7",C:"8",D:"9",ans:"B",exp:"The median is the middle value in an ordered dataset. When the number of values is even, it is calculated as the average of the two middle numbers. Here, (6 + 8) ÷ 2 = 7, making 7 the median of the dataset."},
  {num:56,text:"A patient can recall childhood events but cannot retain new information after a head injury. According to the Multi-Store Model, which system is MOST likely impaired?",A:"Sensory memory",B:"Short-term memory",C:"Long-term memory storage",D:"Transfer from STM to LTM",ans:"D",exp:"The Richard Atkinson and Richard Shiffrin model suggests that inability to form new long-term memories indicates a disruption in the transfer process from short-term memory to long-term memory, often seen in conditions like anterograde amnesia."},
  {num:57,text:"A person feels afraid after noticing their increased heart rate and sweating. This is consistent with:",A:"Cannon-Bard theory",B:"James-Lange theory",C:"Schachter-Singer theory",D:"Lazarus appraisal theory",ans:"B",exp:"The William James–Lange theory proposes that physiological arousal precedes emotional experience. In this case, the person first notices bodily changes like heart rate and sweating, and then interprets these sensations as fear, supporting this theory."},
  {num:58,text:"A test yields consistent scores over time but fails to measure what it intends to measure. This indicates:",A:"High validity, low reliability",B:"High reliability, low validity",C:"Low reliability, high validity",D:"Neither reliability nor validity",ans:"B",exp:"Reliability refers to consistency of measurement, while validity refers to accuracy. A test can consistently produce the same results (high reliability) but still fail to measure the intended construct, indicating low validity. Thus, reliability does not guarantee validity."},
  {num:59,text:"Which disorder was removed as a separate diagnosis and included under Autism Spectrum Disorder in DSM-5?",A:"Rett’s Disorder",B:"Asperger’s Disorder",C:"Childhood Disintegrative Disorder",D:"PDD-NOS",ans:"B",exp:"In the DSM-5, Asperger’s Disorder was merged into Autism Spectrum Disorder. This change reflects a dimensional approach, recognizing varying levels of severity rather than distinct categorical diagnoses within pervasive developmental disorders."},
  {num:60,text:"The independent samples t-test is used when:",A:"The same participants are measured twice",B:"Two unrelated groups are compared",C:"More than two groups are compared",D:"Variables are nominal",ans:"B",exp:"An independent samples t-test compares the means of two separate, unrelated groups to determine if there is a statistically significant difference between them. It is commonly used in experimental research where participants are assigned to different conditions."},
  {num:61,text:"The concept of “ambivalence” in psychopathology coexistence of opposing emotions toward the same object—was introduced by:",A:"Emil Kraepelin",B:"Eugen Bleuler",C:"Erich Fromm",D:"Sigmund Freud",ans:"B",exp:"Eugen Bleuler introduced the concept of ambivalence, particularly in schizophrenia, referring to the simultaneous presence of conflicting emotions or attitudes toward a person, object, or situation, reflecting a disturbance in emotional integration."},
  {num:62,text:"Which feature is characteristic of Obsessive-Compulsive Personality Disorder but NOT OCD?",A:"Repetitive rituals",B:"Ego-dystonic thoughts",C:"Perfectionism seen as appropriate",D:"Intrusive thoughts",ans:"C",exp:"Obsessive-Compulsive Personality Disorder (OCPD) involves ego-syntonic traits such as perfectionism and rigidity, which individuals see as appropriate or desirable. In contrast, OCD involves ego-dystonic obsessions and compulsions that are distressing and recognized as irrational by the individual."},
  {num:63,text:"Which is a key feature of the Mental Healthcare Act, 2017?",A:"Focus on institutionalization",B:"Criminalization of suicide",C:"Right to access mental healthcare",D:"Removal of patient autonomy",ans:"C",exp:"The Mental Healthcare Act, 2017 emphasizes the right to access affordable and quality mental healthcare. It decriminalizes suicide attempts and promotes patient autonomy, dignity, and informed consent in treatment decisions."},
  {num:64,text:"p-value represents:",A:"Probability that null hypothesis is true",B:"Probability of observed result under null hypothesis",C:"Size of effect",D:"Sampling error",ans:"B",exp:"The p-value indicates the probability of obtaining the observed results, or more extreme ones, assuming the null hypothesis is true. It helps determine statistical significance, but does not indicate the truth of the null hypothesis or the magnitude of the effect."},
  {num:65,text:"A persistent delusional belief that one’s partner is unfaithful, often without evidence, is termed:",A:"Ekbom’s syndrome",B:"Othello syndrome",C:"De Clérambault’s syndrome",D:"Couvade syndrome",ans:"B",exp:"Othello syndrome is a form of delusional jealousy where an individual firmly believes their partner is unfaithful despite lack of evidence. It can lead to significant distress and interpersonal conflict and is often associated with psychotic disorders or neurological conditions."},
  {num:66,text:"Electroconvulsive therapy is MOST indicated in:",A:"Mild anxiety",B:"Severe depression with suicidality",C:"Personality disorders",D:"Specific phobia",ans:"B",exp:"Electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) is highly effective for severe depression, especially when accompanied by suicidal risk, psychotic features, or treatment resistance. It provides rapid symptom relief and is often used when medications or psychotherapy are insufficient or too slow in action."},
  {num:67,text:"The use of progressively spaced stripes on roadways to enhance depth perception primarily exploits which monocular cue?",A:"Aerial perspective",B:"Motion parallax",C:"Interposition",D:"Texture gradient",ans:"D",exp:"Texture gradient refers to the visual cue where objects appear denser and finer as they recede into the distance. Road markings use this principle to create an illusion of speed or depth, helping drivers judge distance and adjust their behavior accordingly."},
  {num:68,text:"Under Indian law, a juvenile is defined as:",A:"Below 16 years",B:"Below 18 years",C:"Below 21 years",D:"Below 14 years",ans:"B",exp:"According to the Juvenile Justice (Care and Protection of Children) Act, 2015, a juvenile is any individual below 18 years of age. This definition ensures protection, care, and rehabilitation rather than punishment under the legal system."},
  {num:69,text:"Which condition qualifies as a paraphilic disorder according to DSM-5?",A:"Recurrent sexual fantasies involving unusual objects",B:"Atypical sexual interest without distress",C:"Sexual urges causing distress or harm to others",D:"Non-normative but consensual behavior",ans:"C",exp:"According to the DSM-5, a paraphilic disorder is diagnosed only when atypical sexual interests cause significant distress, impairment, or involve harm or risk to others. Mere atypical interests without these factors are not considered disorders."},
  {num:70,text:"A measurement scale characterized by equal intervals but lacking a true zero point is:",A:"Ratio scale",B:"Ordinal scale",C:"Interval scale",D:"Nominal scale",ans:"C",exp:"An interval scale has equal distances between values, allowing meaningful comparison of differences. However, it lacks a true zero point, meaning ratios are not meaningful. Examples include temperature in Celsius or Fahrenheit, where zero does not indicate absence."},
  {num:71,text:"Which antidepressant is LEAST likely to cause sexual side effects?",A:"Sertraline",B:"Paroxetine",C:"Bupropion",D:"Escitalopram",ans:"C",exp:"Bupropion is known for having minimal sexual side effects compared to SSRIs like sertraline or paroxetine. It acts primarily on dopamine and norepinephrine pathways, making it a preferred option when sexual dysfunction is a concern."},
  {num:72,text:"Which retinal receptors are primarily responsible for vision under low illumination (scotopic vision)?",A:"Cones",B:"Rods",C:"Fovea",D:"Iris",ans:"B",exp:"Rods are specialized photoreceptors in the retina responsible for vision in low-light conditions. They are highly sensitive to light but do not detect color, enabling night vision and peripheral awareness in dim environments."},
  {num:73,text:"Combining SSRIs with which drug class increases risk of serotonin syndrome?",A:"Benzodiazepines",B:"MAO inhibitors",C:"Beta-blockers",D:"Anticholinergics",ans:"B",exp:"Combining SSRIs with monoamine oxidase inhibitors (MAOIs) can lead to excessive serotonin levels, causing serotonin syndrome. This is a potentially life-threatening condition characterized by agitation, confusion, hyperthermia, and neuromuscular abnormalities."},
  {num:74,text:"The perception that parallel railway tracks converge in the distance is BEST classified as:",A:"Permanent illusion",B:"Learned illusion",C:"Müller-Lyer illusion",D:"Linear perspective cue",ans:"D",exp:"Linear perspective is a monocular depth cue where parallel lines appear to converge as they recede into the distance. This visual principle helps the brain interpret depth and distance in the environment, especially in landscapes and roadways."},
  {num:75,text:"The “start–stop” and “squeeze” techniques are behavioral interventions MOST commonly used in:",A:"Erectile disorder",B:"Premature ejaculation",C:"Delayed ejaculation",D:"Vaginismus",ans:"B",exp:"These behavioral techniques are used to manage premature ejaculation by helping individuals gain control over arousal. The start–stop method pauses stimulation, while the squeeze technique reduces arousal, both aiming to delay ejaculation and improve sexual functioning."},
  {num:76,text:"Empirical research typically shows that the correlation between job satisfaction and performance is:",A:"Strong positive",B:"Strong negative",C:"Weak positive",D:"Zero",ans:"C",exp:"Research in organizational psychology consistently finds a weak positive correlation between job satisfaction and performance. While satisfied employees tend to perform slightly better, many other factors like motivation, environment, and ability influence performance, making the relationship modest rather than strong."},
  {num:77,text:"Which is REQUIRED for diagnosis of pedophilic disorder?",A:"Any attraction to minors",B:"Person must be ≥5 years older than the child",C:"Only fantasies",D:"Occasional behavior",ans:"B",exp:"According to the DSM-5, diagnosis requires that the individual is at least five years older than the child and that the urges cause distress, impairment, or involve acting on them. Mere attraction without these criteria is insufficient."},
  {num:78,text:"The term “kleptomania” was originally introduced by:",A:"Marc",B:"Bleuler",C:"Munro",D:"Morselli",ans:"D",exp:"Enrico Morselli introduced the term kleptomania to describe an impulse control disorder characterized by recurrent urges to steal items not needed for personal use or monetary value, driven by internal tension and relief after the act."},
  {num:79,text:"Which brainstem structure plays the MOST critical role in autonomic regulation of respiration and cardiovascular function?",A:"Midbrain",B:"Pons",C:"Medulla oblongata",D:"Reticular activating system",ans:"C",exp:"The medulla oblongata regulates vital autonomic functions such as breathing, heart rate, and blood pressure. It contains essential centers that control respiration and cardiovascular activity, making it critical for survival and basic physiological regulation."},
  {num:80,text:"Hypnagogic hallucinations are MOST commonly experienced:",A:"In schizophrenia",B:"During delirium",C:"In substance dependence",D:"In normal individuals",ans:"D",exp:"Hypnagogic hallucinations occur during the transition from wakefulness to sleep and are commonly experienced by healthy individuals. They are usually visual or auditory and are not necessarily indicative of a psychiatric disorder unless frequent or distressing."},
  {num:81,text:"The tendency to overestimate one’s ability to have predicted an outcome after it is known is called:",A:"Confirmation bias",B:"Hindsight bias",C:"Just-world belief",D:"Overconfidence effect",ans:"B",exp:"Hindsight bias refers to the tendency to believe, after an event has occurred, that one would have predicted it beforehand. This cognitive bias can distort memory and judgment, making outcomes seem more predictable than they actually were."},
  {num:82,text:"Which feature is seen in Reactive Attachment Disorder?",A:"Excessive friendliness",B:"Emotional withdrawal from caregivers",C:"Aggression toward strangers",D:"Hyperactivity",ans:"B",exp:"Reactive Attachment Disorder is characterized by inhibited, emotionally withdrawn behavior toward caregivers. Children show minimal responsiveness, limited positive affect, and reduced seeking of comfort, often due to severe neglect or inconsistent caregiving in early development."},
  {num:83,text:"Reduction of a learned behavior due to withdrawal of reinforcement is termed:",A:"Negative reinforcement",B:"Extinction",C:"Punishment",D:"Reciprocal inhibition",ans:"B",exp:"Extinction occurs when a previously reinforced behavior decreases after the reinforcement is removed. Over time, the behavior weakens and may disappear, reflecting a fundamental principle of learning in both classical and operant conditioning."},
  {num:84,text:"A patient’s depressive episodes become progressively easier to trigger over time, requiring decreasing levels of stressors. This phenomenon is BEST explained by:",A:"Diathesis–stress interaction",B:"Kindling process",C:"Neurotransmitter depletion",D:"Learned helplessness",ans:"B",exp:"The kindling process suggests that repeated episodes of depression lower the threshold for future episodes. Over time, even minor stressors—or none at all—can trigger depressive episodes, indicating increasing biological and psychological sensitization."},
  {num:85,text:"Which neural structure is LEAST directly involved in the cortico-striato-thalamo-cortical circuitry implicated in OCD?",A:"Orbitofrontal cortex",B:"Caudate nucleus",C:"Anterior cingulate cortex",D:"Pons",ans:"D",exp:"The cortico-striato-thalamo-cortical circuit involves cortical and subcortical structures like the orbitofrontal cortex, caudate nucleus, and anterior cingulate cortex. The pons, a brainstem structure, is not directly involved in this circuitry related to obsessive-compulsive disorder."},
  {num:86,text:"Which class of antidepressants works by inhibiting both serotonin and norepinephrine reuptake?",A:"SSRIs",B:"MAOIs",C:"TCAs",D:"SNRIs",ans:"D",exp:"Serotonin-Norepinephrine Reuptake Inhibitors (SNRIs) increase levels of both serotonin and norepinephrine by blocking their reabsorption in the brain. This dual action can improve mood and is commonly used in treating depression and anxiety disorders."},
  {num:87,text:"Which of the following are NOT true about the arithmetic mean?",A:"It is affected by extreme scores",B:"It is the most stable measure",C:"It can be used for nominal data",D:"It is sensitive to outliers",ans:"C",exp:"The arithmetic mean is influenced by extreme scores and is considered a stable measure of central tendency. However, it cannot be used with nominal data because such data lack numerical meaning or order, making calculations like averages inappropriate."},
  {num:88,text:"Neurological impairment in untreated phenylketonuria primarily results from:",A:"Toxic accumulation of phenylalanine in the brain",B:"Dopaminergic excess",C:"Impaired glucose metabolism",D:"Serotonergic dysregulation",ans:"A",exp:"Phenylketonuria (PKU) leads to accumulation of phenylalanine due to a metabolic defect. High levels of this amino acid are toxic to the brain, causing intellectual disability and neurological damage if not treated early through dietary management."},
  {num:89,text:"A patient believes that strangers have been replaced by identical impostors. This delusion is known as:",A:"Fregoli delusion",B:"Capgras syndrome",C:"Cotard syndrome",D:"Othello syndrome",ans:"B",exp:"Capgras syndrome is a delusional misidentification disorder where familiar individuals are believed to be replaced by impostors. It is often associated with neurological or psychiatric conditions affecting face recognition and emotional processing."},
  {num:90,text:"Which symptom is considered a negative symptom of schizophrenia?",A:"Hallucination",B:"Delusion",C:"Avolition",D:"Disorganized speech",ans:"C",exp:"Avolition refers to a lack of motivation or inability to initiate goal-directed behavior. It is a negative symptom of schizophrenia, indicating a reduction or absence of normal functions, unlike positive symptoms such as hallucinations or delusions."},
  {num:91,text:"Who is regarded as the “Father of Indian Psychology”?",A:"Girindrasekhar Bose",B:"Narendra Nath Sen Gupta",C:"Durganand Sinha",D:"B. F. Skinner",ans:"B",exp:"Narendra Nath Sen Gupta is considered the Father of Indian Psychology for his pioneering role in establishing experimental psychology in India and promoting indigenous psychological thought."},
  {num:92,text:"Cotard’s syndrome involves:",A:"Belief that one is being persecuted",B:"Belief that one is dead or does not exist",C:"Fear of open spaces",D:"Repetitive intrusive thoughts",ans:"B",exp:"Cotard’s syndrome is a rare delusional condition where individuals believe they are dead, nonexistent, or have lost their organs. It is often associated with severe depression and psychotic disorders."},
  {num:93,text:"A patient presents with chronic insecurity and lack of grounding. Dysfunction in which chakra is implicated?",A:"Vishuddha",B:"Ajna",C:"Muladhara",D:"Sahasrara",ans:"C",exp:"The Muladhara (root chakra) is linked to safety, stability, and basic survival needs. Dysfunction may lead to fear, insecurity, and lack of grounding."},
  {num:94,text:"The concept of “Anomie” was introduced by:",A:"Émile Durkheim",B:"Sigmund Freud",C:"Ivan Pavlov",D:"B. F. Skinner",ans:"A",exp:"Émile Durkheim introduced anomie to describe a state of normlessness where social norms break down, leading to confusion and instability in individuals."},
  {num:95,text:"Disturbance in the Anahata (heart) chakra leads to:",A:"Impaired reality testing",B:"Emotional detachment and difficulty forming attachments",C:"Excessive sexual impulsivity",D:"Disturbance in speech",ans:"B",exp:"The Anahata chakra governs love, compassion, and emotional bonding. Imbalance may result in emotional coldness, difficulty trusting, and relational issues."},
  {num:96,text:"Excess dominance of Rajas guna is associated with:",A:"Lethargy and apathy",B:"Hyperactivity, anxiety, restlessness",C:"Emotional stability and clarity",D:"Detachment",ans:"B",exp:"In yogic psychology, Rajas represents activity and energy. When excessive, it manifests as agitation, impulsivity, and restlessness."},
  {num:97,text:"MATCH THE FOLLOWING – Behavioral Psychology [TABLE] | **List I (Concept)** | **List II (Description)** | | | --- | --- | | | A. Positive Reinforcement | 2. Adding pleasant stimulus to increase behavior | | | B. Negative Reinforcement | 1. Removal of unpleasant stimulus to increase behavior | | | C. Punishment (Type I) | 3. Adding unpleasant stimulus to decrease behavior | | | D. Punishment (Type II) | 4. Removing pleasant stimulus to decrease behavior |",A:"Option A",B:"Option B",C:"Option C",D:"Option D",ans:"C",exp:"Reinforcement increases behavior, while punishment decreases it. Positive reinforcement adds a reward; negative reinforcement removes an aversive stimulus. Punishment Type I introduces an unpleasant consequence, whereas Type II removes a pleasant stimulus. These principles, rooted in operant conditioning by B. F. Skinner, explain behavior modification."},
  {num:98,text:"Assertion–Reason Assertion (A): Schema-driven processing can lead to memory distortions. Reason (R): Schemas influence encoding and retrieval.",A:"Both Assertion and Reason are true, and Reason correctly explains Assertion",B:"Both true, but Reason does NOT explain Assertion",C:"Assertion true, Reason false",D:"Assertion false, Reason true",ans:"A",exp:"Schemas act as mental frameworks shaping how information is processed. They influence both encoding and retrieval, which can distort memory by filling gaps or biasing recall toward expectations."},
  {num:99,text:"MATCH THE FOLLOWING – Positive Psychology [TABLE] | **List I (Concept)** | **List II (Meaning)** | | | --- | --- | | | A. Flow | 1. Deep engagement with loss of self-consciousness | | | B. Resilience | 2. Ability to bounce back from adversity | | | C. Gratitude | 3. Appreciation of positive aspects | | | D. Optimism | 4. Expectation of positive outcomes |",A:"Option A",B:"Option B",C:"Option C",D:"Option D",ans:"A",exp:"Positive psychology focuses on strengths and well-being. Flow involves deep immersion in tasks (coined by Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi). Resilience is recovery from adversity, gratitude enhances well-being through appreciation, and optimism reflects positive expectations about the future, all contributing to psychological flourishing."},
  {num:100,text:"Assertion–Reason Assertion (A): In figure-ground perception, the figure is always smaller than the ground. Reason (R): Figure-ground organization depends only on size differences.",A:"Both Assertion and Reason are true, and Reason correctly explains Assertion",B:"Both true, but Reason does NOT explain Assertion",C:"Assertion true, Reason false",D:"Assertion false, Reason true",ans:"D",exp:"The assertion is false because figure-ground perception depends on multiple factors like contrast, symmetry, and familiarity—not just size. The reason is also incorrect in stating “only size,” but among given options, D is considered the closest (Reason true in limited sense, Assertion false)."}
];

const TEST2_DATA = // Mock Test 2
[
  {num:1,text:"A patient following a right hemisphere stroke demonstrates neglect of the left side of space, failing to draw the left half of a clock face. This phenomenon is BEST described as:",A:"Prosopagnosia",B:"Hemispatial neglect",C:"Simultanagnosia",D:"Visual field defect",ans:"B",exp:"Hemispatial neglect (unilateral neglect) typically results from right parietal lobe damage and leads to failure to attend to stimuli on the contralateral (left) side of space. The clock-drawing task is a classic clinical demonstration of this deficit."},
  {num:2,text:"Which cranial nerve is primarily responsible for transmitting auditory information from the cochlea to the brain?",A:"CN V (Trigeminal)",B:"CN VII (Facial)",C:"CN VIII (Vestibulocochlear)",D:"CN IX (Glossopharyngeal)",ans:"C",exp:"The vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII) carries sensory information for both hearing (cochlear branch) and balance (vestibular branch) to the brainstem. Damage to this nerve can result in sensorineural hearing loss or vestibular disturbances."},
  {num:3,text:"The 'Alien Hand Syndrome,' where one hand acts seemingly independently of conscious will, most commonly results from lesions to the:",A:"Cerebellum",B:"Corpus callosum or supplementary motor area",C:"Thalamus",D:"Occipital cortex",ans:"B",exp:"Syndrome is classically associated with lesions of the corpus callosum (particularly following callosotomy) or the supplementary motor area. Disconnection prevents one hemisphere from knowing what the other is doing, causing the contralateral hand to act involuntarily."},
  {num:4,text:"Which neuropsychological test requires a subject to sort cards based on hidden rules and shift sorting strategy as rules change, primarily assessing executive function?",A:"Trail Making Test",B:"Rey Auditory Verbal Learning Test",C:"Wisconsin Card Sorting Test",D:"Stroop Color-Word Test",ans:"C",exp:"Test (WCST) is a classic test of executive function, particularly cognitive flexibility and the ability to shift set. It is sensitive to frontal lobe dysfunction. Perseverative errors (continuing to sort by an old rule) are the hallmark of frontal impairment."},
  {num:5,text:"Damage to the right fusiform face area most characteristically produces:",A:"Broca's aphasia",B:"Prosopagnosia",C:"Wernicke's aphasia",D:"Achromatopsia",ans:"B",exp:"Prosopagnosia (face blindness) is the inability to recognize familiar faces. It is most commonly associated with bilateral or right-hemisphere lesions of the fusiform gyrus in the temporal-occipital junction."},
  {num:6,text:"The Halstead-Reitan Battery is BEST described as:",A:"A projective personality test",B:"A comprehensive neuropsychological battery assessing brain-behavior relationships",C:"A structured clinical interview for DSM diagnosis",D:"An intelligence test standardized for Indian populations",ans:"B",exp:"Battery (HRB) is one of the most widely used comprehensive neuropsychological assessment tools. It evaluates various cognitive and sensory-motor functions to identify and localize brain damage, and to assess the effects of brain injury or disease."},
  {num:7,text:"A patient with intact primary visual cortex reports blindness but demonstrates accurate motor responses (e.g., reaching) to visual stimuli. This is known as:",A:"Cortical blindness",B:"Blindsight",C:"Anton's syndrome",D:"Optic ataxia",ans:"B",exp:"Blindsight occurs when patients with damage to the primary visual cortex (V1) can respond to visual stimuli without consciously perceiving them. It is thought to depend on subcortical visual pathways (e.g., superior colliculus). Anton's syndrome, by contrast, is cortical blindness with anosognosia."},
  {num:8,text:"Which of the following is the MOST direct consequence of bilateral hippocampal damage?",A:"Loss of procedural memory",B:"Severe anterograde amnesia with spared remote memory",C:"Global aphasia",D:"Loss of emotional processing",ans:"B",exp:"Bilateral hippocampal damage (as in patient H.M.) produces profound anterograde amnesia — the inability to form new declarative memories — while procedural memory and remote long-term memories largely remain intact. This dissociation provided foundational evidence for memory systems theory."},
  {num:9,text:"All of the following are associated with parietal lobe damage EXCEPT:",A:"Gerstmann's syndrome",B:"Constructional apraxia",C:"Contralateral sensory loss",D:"Personality change and impulsivity",ans:"D",exp:"Personality changes, impulsivity, and impaired social judgment are hallmarks of frontal lobe (especially orbitofrontal cortex) damage. Parietal lobe damage characteristically produces Gerstmann's syndrome (finger agnosia, acalculia, agraphia, left-right disorientation), constructional apraxia, and contralateral sensory loss."},
  {num:10,text:"Which neuroimaging technique directly measures neuronal activity via blood oxygen level-dependent (BOLD) contrast?",A:"PET scan",B:"CT scan",C:"fMRI",D:"EEG",ans:"C",exp:"MRI (fMRI) measures brain activity by detecting changes in blood oxygenation (BOLD signal). When neurons are active, they consume oxygen, triggering local increases in oxygenated blood flow, which alters the MRI signal. PET scans measure glucose metabolism or radiotracer distribution."},
  {num:11,text:"Transcortical motor aphasia is characterized by:",A:"Non-fluent spontaneous speech with intact repetition and good comprehension",B:"Fluent paraphasic speech with impaired repetition",C:"Complete loss of all language modalities",D:"Intact spontaneous speech with impaired repetition",ans:"A",exp:"Transcortical motor aphasia is a non-fluent aphasia where spontaneous speech is reduced but repetition is remarkably preserved (unlike Broca's aphasia). Comprehension is relatively intact. It results from lesions anterior/superior to Broca's area, sparing the perisylvian language zone."},
  {num:12,text:"The cerebellum's primary role in motor function is:",A:"Initiating voluntary movements",B:"Coordinating smooth movement and maintaining balance",C:"Processing pain signals",D:"Regulating autonomic responses",ans:"B",exp:"The cerebellum is critical for coordination of smooth, precise voluntary movements, balance, and motor learning. Cerebellar damage produces ataxia, dysmetria, and intention tremor rather than paralysis, as the cerebellum modulates movement rather than initiating it."},
  {num:13,text:"According to DSM-5, for a diagnosis of Major Depressive Disorder, depressive symptoms must be present for at least:",A:"1 week",B:"2 weeks",C:"1 month",D:"6 months",ans:"B",exp:"(b) 2 weeks DSM-5 requires that at least five depressive symptoms (including depressed mood or anhedonia) be present nearly every day for a minimum of two weeks. This minimum duration distinguishes MDD from transient depressive reactions."},
  {num:14,text:"Folie à deux (shared psychotic disorder) is now classified under which category in DSM-5?",A:"Delusional Disorder",B:"Schizophrenia Spectrum and Other Psychotic Disorders",C:"Somatic Symptom Disorders",D:"Dissociative Disorders",ans:"B",exp:"DSM-5, Folie à deux has been removed as a separate category and is now captured under 'Other Specified Schizophrenia Spectrum and Other Psychotic Disorder.' It involves a shared delusional belief induced in a closely associated person by another with an established psychotic disorder."},
  {num:15,text:"Which of the following is the HALLMARK distinguishing feature of Borderline Personality Disorder from other personality disorders?",A:"Persistent grandiosity",B:"Pervasive pattern of instability in affect, self-image, and interpersonal relationships with frantic efforts to avoid abandonment",C:"Detachment from social relationships",D:"Preoccupation with orderliness",ans:"B",exp:"BPD (DSM-5) is characterized by a pervasive pattern of instability in interpersonal relationships, self-image, and affect, along with impulsivity. Frantic efforts to avoid real or imagined abandonment and identity disturbance are central features, distinguishing it from NPD, schizoid, or OCPD."},
  {num:16,text:"In DSM-5, which anxiety disorder is characterized by persistent, excessive worry about multiple life domains lasting at least 6 months?",A:"Panic Disorder",B:"Social Anxiety Disorder",C:"Generalized Anxiety Disorder",D:"Specific Phobia",ans:"C",exp:"Disorder (GAD) is defined by excessive, difficult-to-control worry about various topics (work, health, family) occurring more days than not for at least 6 months, accompanied by somatic symptoms like restlessness, fatigue, and sleep disturbance."},
  {num:17,text:"Which of the following is a positive symptom of schizophrenia?",A:"Alogia",B:"Avolition",C:"Thought insertion",D:"Flat affect",ans:"C",exp:"Positive symptoms reflect an excess or distortion of normal functions and include hallucinations, delusions, disorganized speech, and thought insertion/broadcasting. Alogia, avolition, and flat affect are negative symptoms reflecting diminishment of normal functions."},
  {num:18,text:"Munchausen syndrome is now referred to in DSM-5 as:",A:"Somatic Symptom Disorder",B:"Factitious Disorder Imposed on Self",C:"Illness Anxiety Disorder",D:"Conversion Disorder",ans:"B",exp:"DSM-5 renamed Munchausen syndrome to Factitious Disorder Imposed on Self. Individuals intentionally feign or induce illness symptoms for psychological reasons (to assume the sick role), without external incentives, distinguishing it from malingering."},
  {num:19,text:"A 45-year-old man presents with involuntary, irregular writhing movements of the limbs, progressive cognitive decline, and a family history of similar illness. The MOST likely diagnosis is:",A:"Parkinson's disease",B:"Huntington's disease",C:"Multiple sclerosis",D:"Wilson's disease",ans:"B",exp:"Huntington's disease is an autosomal dominant neurodegenerative disorder presenting with chorea (involuntary writhing movements), psychiatric symptoms, and progressive dementia, typically in midlife. It is caused by a CAG trinucleotide repeat expansion in the HTT gene."},
  {num:20,text:"In ICD-11, 'Complex PTSD' differs from PTSD by including which additional cluster of symptoms?",A:"Flashbacks and hyperarousal",B:"Disturbances in self-organization (DSO): affect dysregulation, negative self-concept, and interpersonal disturbances",C:"Dissociative amnesia",D:"Avoidance of trauma-related stimuli",ans:"B",exp:"(b) Disturbances in self-organization (DSO): affect dysregulation, negative self-concept, and interpersonal disturbances ICD-11 introduced Complex PTSD, which includes the core PTSD symptoms PLUS disturbances in self-organization (DSO): pervasive problems with emotion regulation, persistent negative beliefs about the self, and difficulties in sustaining relationships. These are common sequelae of prolonged or repeated trauma."},
  {num:21,text:"The learned helplessness model of depression was originally developed by:",A:"Aaron Beck",B:"Martin Seligman",C:"Albert Ellis",D:"Carl Rogers",ans:"B",exp:"Seligman's learned helplessness theory proposed that depression results from repeated exposure to uncontrollable events, leading individuals to believe their actions have no effect on outcomes. This model was later refined by Abramson, Seligman, and Teasdale into the attributional reformulation."},
  {num:22,text:"Delirium is distinguished from dementia PRIMARILY by:",A:"Presence of hallucinations",B:"Memory impairment",C:"Acute onset and fluctuating level of consciousness",D:"Personality changes",ans:"C",exp:"The key distinguishing features of delirium are its acute onset (hours to days), fluctuating course, and disturbance of consciousness/attention. Dementia has an insidious onset with progressive but not typically fluctuating deficits. Both can involve hallucinations and memory problems."},
  {num:23,text:"Which of the following pairs correctly matches the anxiety disorder with its key cognitive distortion?",A:"OCD — overestimation of physical danger",B:"Health Anxiety — thought-action fusion",C:"Social Anxiety Disorder — mind reading and negative evaluation",D:"Panic Disorder — jumping to conclusions about social rejection",ans:"C",exp:"Disorder — mind reading and negative evaluation Social Anxiety Disorder is driven by cognitive distortions such as mind reading (assuming others think negatively), negative evaluation apprehension, and the spotlight effect. OCD is associated with thought-action fusion and inflated responsibility. Panic Disorder involves catastrophic misinterpretation of bodily sensations."},
  {num:24,text:"Schneiderian First-Rank Symptoms are pathognomonic of:",A:"Bipolar disorder",B:"Schizophrenia",C:"Depersonalization disorder",D:"Dissociative identity disorder",ans:"B",exp:"Symptoms (e.g., thought insertion, thought withdrawal, thought broadcasting, passivity experiences, voices commenting) as highly specific for schizophrenia. Though no longer considered pathognomonic in DSM-5, they remain clinically important diagnostic indicators."},
  {num:25,text:"All of the following are specifiers used for Major Depressive Disorder in DSM-5 EXCEPT:",A:"With anxious distress",B:"With melancholic features",C:"With mixed features",D:"With prodromal features",ans:"D",exp:"DSM-5 specifiers for MDD include 'with anxious distress,' 'with melancholic features,' 'with mixed features,' 'with psychotic features,' 'with catatonia,' 'with atypical features,' and 'with peripartum onset.' 'Prodromal features' is not a recognized DSM-5 specifier."},
  {num:26,text:"In the context of substance use disorders, which term describes the subjective compulsion to use a substance that occupies a central place in DSM-5 but was absent in DSM-IV?",A:"Tolerance",B:"Withdrawal",C:"Craving",D:"Dependence",ans:"C",exp:"DSM-5 added 'craving' as a diagnostic criterion for Substance Use Disorders, replacing the DSM-IV's legal problems criterion. Craving refers to a strong desire or urge to use a substance and is recognized as a core feature of addiction."},
  {num:27,text:"A client repeatedly checks that the gas stove is off despite knowing it is off, driven by intolerable anxiety. This most accurately reflects:",A:"Paranoid ideation",B:"Compulsive behavior with obsessional doubt",C:"Hypochondriasis",D:"Ritualistic behavior secondary to psychosis",ans:"B",exp:"OCD pattern: an intrusive obsessional doubt (gas might be on) drives repetitive checking compulsions to neutralize anxiety. Insight is preserved (the person knows the stove is off), distinguishing it from psychosis-driven rituals."},
  {num:28,text:"Which of the following BEST describes the concept of 'anosognosia'?",A:"Inability to name objects",B:"Lack of awareness of one's own neurological deficit or illness",C:"Difficulty in reading and writing",D:"Impaired calculation ability",ans:"B",exp:"Anosognosia is the lack of awareness or denial of a neurological or psychiatric deficit. It is common in right hemisphere strokes (where patients deny hemiplegia) and in severe mental illness. It significantly impacts treatment compliance and outcomes."},
  {num:29,text:"Persistent depressive disorder (Dysthymia) in DSM-5 requires symptoms to be present for at least:",A:"1 month in adults",B:"6 months in adults",C:"2 years in adults",D:"1 year in children only",ans:"C",exp:"(c) 2 years in adults DSM-5 Persistent Depressive Disorder (which merged Dysthymia and Chronic MDD) requires depressed mood for most of the day, more days than not, for at least 2 years in adults (1 year in children and adolescents), with associated symptoms."},
  {num:30,text:"The 'undoing' defense mechanism involves:",A:"Redirecting unacceptable impulses toward a safer target",B:"Symbolically acting out the opposite of an unacceptable impulse to negate it",C:"Transforming negative emotions into positive actions",D:"Denying the existence of unacceptable urges",ans:"B",exp:"Undoing is a defense mechanism where a person symbolically performs an act that 'cancels out' or negates a previous unacceptable thought or behavior. It is classically seen in OCD, where compulsive acts (e.g., cleaning) undo the anxiety caused by intrusive thoughts."},
  {num:31,text:"Ganser syndrome is characterized by:",A:"Multiple personality states",B:"Approximate answers (Vorbeireden), psychogenic physical symptoms, and clouded consciousness",C:"Severe anterograde amnesia following alcohol use",D:"Pseudoseizures secondary to conversion disorder",ans:"B",exp:"(b) Approximate answers (Vorbeireden), psychogenic physical symptoms, and clouded consciousness Ganser syndrome is a rare dissociative condition classically featuring 'approximate answers' (Vorbeireden — e.g., answering '5' when asked '2+2=?'), along with pseudo-hallucinations, somatic conversion symptoms, and apparent clouding of consciousness. It is sometimes seen in prisoners."},
  {num:32,text:"Which of the following is the FIRST-LINE psychological treatment for PTSD recommended by most international guidelines?",A:"Psychodynamic therapy",B:"Trauma-Focused Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (TF-CBT)",C:"Supportive counseling",D:"Schema therapy",ans:"B",exp:"Therapy (TF-CBT) Trauma-Focused CBT (TF-CBT) and EMDR are recommended as first-line psychological treatments for PTSD by WHO, NICE, and APA guidelines. They involve systematic processing of traumatic memories and reducing avoidance, which maintains PTSD symptoms."},
  {num:33,text:"Which of the following phenomena is characteristic of dissociative identity disorder (DID) but NOT of schizophrenia?",A:"Auditory hallucinations",B:"Amnesia for personal history and identity-based behavioral shifts",C:"Social withdrawal",D:"Delusions",ans:"B",exp:"DID and schizophrenia may involve hearing voices, identity-based amnesia and distinct personality states (alters) with behavioral shifts are hallmarks of DID. In schizophrenia, voices are typically experienced as external, while in DID they often feel like internal alters."},
  {num:34,text:"A 28-year-old woman exercises 3 hours daily, has BMI 16.5, refuses to gain weight despite being underweight, and denies illness. The MOST accurate diagnosis is:",A:"Bulimia nervosa",B:"Anorexia nervosa, restricting type",C:"Binge-eating disorder",D:"Body dysmorphic disorder",ans:"B",exp:"Anorexia nervosa (restricting type) is characterized by severe restriction of energy intake, resulting in significantly low body weight, intense fear of gaining weight, and disturbed body image with denial of the seriousness of low weight. The absence of binge/purge episodes points to the restricting subtype."},
  {num:35,text:"A researcher wants to study the lived experiences of refugees in India without imposing pre-existing categories. The MOST appropriate qualitative approach is:",A:"Grounded Theory",B:"Phenomenology",C:"Ethnography",D:"Content Analysis",ans:"B",exp:"Phenomenology aims to describe and understand the subjective, lived experience of a phenomenon from the perspective of those who experience it, without imposing prior theoretical frameworks. It is ideal for exploring depth of personal experience, such as the lived experience of refugees."},
  {num:36,text:"Which of the following research designs has the HIGHEST internal validity?",A:"Case study",B:"Correlational study",C:"True experimental design with random assignment",D:"Naturalistic observation",ans:"C",exp:"A true experimental design with random assignment to conditions has the highest internal validity because randomization controls for both known and unknown confounding variables, allowing confident causal inferences. Other designs lack this control."},
  {num:37,text:"In a double-blind study, who is kept unaware of the condition assignment?",A:"Only the participants",B:"Only the researchers",C:"Both participants and the researchers administering the intervention",D:"Only the data analyst",ans:"C",exp:"In a double-blind design, neither the participants nor the researchers directly interacting with them know which condition (experimental or control) each participant is in. This prevents both placebo effects and experimenter bias from confounding the results."},
  {num:38,text:"Which of the following BEST defines face validity?",A:"The degree to which a test predicts a future criterion",B:"The extent to which test content represents the domain being measured",C:"The superficial appearance of a test as measuring what it claims to measure",D:"The degree to which a test correlates with established measures of the same construct",ans:"C",exp:"Face validity refers to the extent to which a test appears, on the surface, to measure what it is intended to measure. It is the most subjective form of validity, based on the judgment of lay persons or test takers, not empirical evidence."},
  {num:39,text:"In a study examining the relationship between childhood trauma and adult depression, childhood trauma is the:",A:"Dependent variable",B:"Extraneous variable",C:"Independent variable",D:"Moderating variable",ans:"C",exp:"In this study, childhood trauma is hypothesized to influence adult depression. The variable that is presumed to cause or predict the outcome is the independent variable (predictor). Adult depression, being the outcome, is the dependent variable."},
  {num:40,text:"Triangulation in qualitative research refers to:",A:"Using three separate statistical tests on the same data",B:"Using multiple data sources, methods, or investigators to enhance credibility",C:"Selecting a sample of exactly three participants for a case study",D:"Analyzing data at three levels of abstraction",ans:"B",exp:"Triangulation improves the credibility (trustworthiness) of qualitative research by using multiple data sources (data triangulation), methods (methodological triangulation), or investigators (investigator triangulation). Convergence of findings across these enhances confidence in conclusions."},
  {num:41,text:"A Type II error in hypothesis testing refers to:",A:"Rejecting a true null hypothesis",B:"Failing to reject a false null hypothesis",C:"Using the wrong statistical test",D:"Overfitting the model to data",ans:"B",exp:"II error (β error) occurs when a researcher fails to reject a null hypothesis that is actually false — i.e., missing a real effect. The probability of a Type II error is β, and power (1-β) is the probability of correctly detecting a true effect."},
  {num:42,text:"Criterion validity can be divided into:",A:"Content and construct validity",B:"Concurrent and predictive validity",C:"Face and ecological validity",D:"Convergent and discriminant validity",ans:"B",exp:"Criterion validity is assessed by correlating a test score with an external criterion. Concurrent validity is assessed when criterion data are available at the same time as the test, while predictive validity assesses how well the test predicts a future criterion outcome."},
  {num:43,text:"The Hawthorne Effect refers to:",A:"Participants performing better because they know they are being observed",B:"The tendency of researchers to find what they expect to find",C:"A reduction in performance over time in longitudinal studies",D:"Carryover effects in within-subjects designs",ans:"A",exp:"Effect is the phenomenon whereby individuals alter their behavior simply because they are aware of being observed or participating in research. It was first noted in studies at the Hawthorne Works factory in Illinois and represents a significant threat to internal validity."},
  {num:44,text:"Assigning a rank ordering of '1st, 2nd, 3rd' to participants based on performance level reflects which scale of measurement?",A:"Nominal scale",B:"Ordinal scale",C:"Interval scale",D:"Ratio scale",ans:"B",exp:"Ordinal scales rank-order data without assuming equal intervals between ranks. While we know 1st is better than 2nd, we cannot say the difference between 1st and 2nd equals the difference between 2nd and 3rd. Rankings, grades, and Likert-type scales are common examples."},
  {num:45,text:"Which of the following sampling methods ensures proportional representation of subgroups in the sample?",A:"Simple random sampling",B:"Stratified random sampling",C:"Snowball sampling",D:"Purposive sampling",ans:"B",exp:"Stratified random sampling divides the population into homogeneous subgroups (strata) and randomly samples from each stratum in proportion to its size. This ensures the sample reflects the population's composition and increases statistical efficiency."},
  {num:46,text:"In research ethics, the principle of 'beneficence' means:",A:"Respecting the autonomy of research participants",B:"Ensuring research does not harm participants",C:"Maximizing benefits and minimizing harms for participants",D:"Ensuring fair distribution of research burdens and benefits",ans:"C",exp:"Beneficence requires researchers to maximize benefits and minimize potential harms to participants. It goes beyond simply avoiding harm (non-maleficence) to actively promoting participant well-being. Justice refers to equitable distribution; autonomy is respected through informed consent."},
  {num:47,text:"A distribution where the mean equals the median equals the mode is called:",A:"Negatively skewed",B:"Positively skewed",C:"Normal (symmetrical) distribution",D:"Bimodal distribution",ans:"C",exp:"(c) Normal (symmetrical) distribution In a perfectly normal distribution, the mean, median, and mode are all equal and located at the center. In positively skewed distributions, the mean > median > mode. In negatively skewed distributions, the mean < median < mode."},
  {num:48,text:"When comparing means of three or more independent groups, the appropriate parametric statistical test is:",A:"Independent samples t-test",B:"Pearson's correlation",C:"One-way ANOVA",D:"Chi-square test",ans:"C",exp:"ANOVA (Analysis of Variance) is used to compare means across three or more independent groups. Using multiple t-tests inflates the Type I error rate (familywise error). ANOVA tests whether any group mean differs significantly from the others."},
  {num:49,text:"The Kruskal-Wallis test is the non-parametric equivalent of:",A:"Independent samples t-test",B:"One-way ANOVA",C:"Paired samples t-test",D:"Pearson's correlation",ans:"B",exp:"ANOVA. It is used when the assumptions of ANOVA (normality and homogeneity of variance) are not met, or when the dependent variable is measured on an ordinal scale."},
  {num:50,text:"A Pearson correlation of r = -0.85 between anxiety and academic performance indicates:",A:"A weak negative relationship",B:"A strong positive relationship",C:"A strong negative relationship",D:"No meaningful relationship",ans:"C",exp:"Pearson r of -0.85 indicates a strong (close to -1.0) negative correlation, meaning higher anxiety is strongly associated with lower academic performance. The sign indicates direction; the magnitude (0.85) indicates strength. Values above 0.70 are generally considered strong."},
  {num:51,text:"In factor analysis, the proportion of a variable's variance explained by the common factors is termed:",A:"Eigenvalue",B:"Factor loading",C:"Communality",D:"Scree value",ans:"C",exp:"Communality (h²) represents the proportion of each observed variable's variance that is accounted for by the extracted common factors. A high communality indicates the variable is well-represented by the factor solution. Factor loadings show how strongly each variable relates to each factor."},
  {num:52,text:"In regression analysis, a Beta (β) coefficient of 0.65 for variable X predicting Y indicates:",A:"X causes Y with 65% certainty",B:"For every 1 SD increase in X, Y increases by 0.65 SD, holding other variables constant",C:"65% of the variance in Y is explained by X",D:"X and Y have a correlation of 0.65",ans:"B",exp:"(b) For every 1 SD increase in X, Y increases by 0.65 SD, holding other variables constant The standardized beta coefficient (β) in regression indicates how many standard deviations Y changes for every one standard deviation change in X, after controlling for other predictors. It allows comparison of the relative contributions of different predictors in the same model."},
  {num:53,text:"Which of the following is a NON-parametric test for assessing correlation between two ordinal variables?",A:"Pearson's r",B:"Spearman's rho",C:"Point-biserial correlation",D:"Intraclass correlation",ans:"B",exp:"Spearman's rank-order correlation (rho) is a non-parametric measure of association suitable for ordinal data or interval data that violates normality assumptions. It measures the degree of monotonic relationship between two variables using ranked data."},
  {num:54,text:"The standard error of the mean (SEM) will DECREASE as:",A:"Sample variance increases",B:"Sample size increases",C:"Population standard deviation increases",D:"The null hypothesis is rejected",ans:"B",exp:"SEM = SD / √n. As sample size (n) increases, the denominator grows, reducing the SEM. This means larger samples provide more precise estimates of the population mean. Increased variance or SD would increase the SEM."},
  {num:55,text:"George Miller's 'magical number seven, plus or minus two' refers to:",A:"The number of long-term memory stores",B:"The capacity of short-term (working) memory",C:"The number of cognitive development stages",D:"The ideal number of response options in a Likert scale",ans:"B",exp:"(b) The capacity of short-term (working) memory George Miller (1956) proposed that short-term memory capacity is approximately 7 ± 2 chunks of information. 'Chunking' — grouping individual items into meaningful units — allows more information to be held within this limited capacity."},
  {num:56,text:"The phonological loop in Baddeley's Working Memory Model is responsible for:",A:"Storing visuospatial information",B:"Coordinating the subsidiary systems",C:"Temporarily storing and rehearsing verbal/phonological information",D:"Linking working memory with long-term memory",ans:"C",exp:"(c) Temporarily storing and rehearsing verbal/phonological information Baddeley's Working Memory Model (1974) includes the phonological loop (verbal/phonological short-term storage and rehearsal), the visuospatial sketchpad (visual/spatial information), the central executive (attentional control), and the episodic buffer (linking to LTM)."},
  {num:57,text:"Which of the following BEST illustrates the 'depth of processing' effect proposed by Craik and Lockhart?",A:"Repeating a word 10 times leads to better recall than thinking about its meaning",B:"Words processed for their meaning are better recalled than those processed only for their sound",C:"Visual images are always remembered better than words",D:"The primacy effect is stronger than the recency effect",ans:"B",exp:"Processing framework proposes that deeper semantic processing produces more durable memory traces than shallow phonological or structural processing. Thinking about a word's meaning (semantic) produces better retention than merely rehearsing its sound."},
  {num:58,text:"The tendency to recall items from the beginning of a list more accurately is known as:",A:"Recency effect",B:"Primacy effect",C:"Encoding specificity principle",D:"Serial position effect",ans:"B",exp:"The primacy effect refers to superior recall of items from the beginning of a list, attributed to their transfer into long-term memory due to rehearsal. The recency effect refers to better recall of the last few items due to them still residing in short-term memory."},
  {num:59,text:"Which concept describes the cognitive tendency to interpret new information in terms of existing knowledge structures?",A:"Accommodation",B:"Assimilation",C:"Equilibration",D:"Scaffolding",ans:"B",exp:"Assimilation (Piaget) occurs when new information is incorporated into existing schemas without modifying them. Accommodation occurs when schemas must change to incorporate new information that doesn't fit. These two processes work together toward equilibration."},
  {num:60,text:"The 'availability heuristic' refers to:",A:"Judging probability based on representative features of a category",B:"Estimating frequency or probability based on how easily examples come to mind",C:"Making decisions based on the first piece of information encountered",D:"Solving problems by working backward from the goal",ans:"B",exp:"Tversky's availability heuristic involves estimating the likelihood of events based on how quickly examples come to mind. Events that are vivid, recent, or emotionally charged are cognitively more available and are therefore perceived as more probable."},
  {num:61,text:"In Atkinson and Shiffrin's multi-store model, the capacity of sensory memory is:",A:"7 ± 2 chunks",B:"Very limited (1-2 items)",C:"Large but very brief (fractions of a second)",D:"Unlimited and permanent",ans:"C",exp:"(c) Large but very brief (fractions of a second) Sensory memory (iconic for vision, echoic for hearing) has a very large capacity but an extremely brief duration (< 1 second for iconic, 2-4 seconds for echoic). It holds a faithful representation of the sensory input before selective attention transfers some information to short-term memory."},
  {num:62,text:"The Stroop effect demonstrates:",A:"The superiority of visual over verbal processing",B:"Interference between automatic and controlled processing",C:"The capacity limit of working memory",D:"The role of schemas in perception",ans:"B",exp:"Stroop effect shows that naming the ink color of a color word (e.g., 'RED' written in blue ink) is slower and more error-prone than naming a neutral stimulus's color. This occurs because reading is an automatic process that interferes with the controlled task of naming ink color."},
  {num:63,text:"Metacognition is BEST defined as:",A:"Thinking about emotions and their regulation",B:"Knowing about and regulating one's own cognitive processes",C:"The ability to think abstractly about hypothetical situations",D:"Long-term memory for general world knowledge",ans:"B",exp:"Metacognition, often called 'thinking about thinking,' involves awareness and regulation of one's own cognitive processes. It includes metacognitive knowledge (what one knows about cognition) and metacognitive regulation (monitoring and controlling learning strategies)."},
  {num:64,text:"Which of the following BEST describes 'functional fixedness'?",A:"The inability to shift from one problem-solving strategy to another",B:"The cognitive bias of perceiving objects only in terms of their traditional use",C:"Continuing to apply a strategy that worked previously even when it is no longer efficient",D:"Overestimating one's ability to solve a problem based on past success",ans:"B",exp:"Functional fixedness is a cognitive bias where a person can only perceive an object's function in its conventional use, limiting creative problem solving. Classic demonstrations include Duncker's candle problem. It contrasts with the mental set (Einstellung), which involves rigidly applying old problem-solving approaches."},
  {num:65,text:"Social loafing refers to:",A:"Increased effort when working in front of others",B:"The tendency of individuals to exert less effort when working in a group",C:"Conforming to group norms to avoid social rejection",D:"Aggression triggered by social frustration",ans:"B",exp:"Social loafing (Latané, Williams, & Harkins, 1979) is the tendency for individuals to put in less effort on a collective task compared to working alone, partly due to diffused accountability and reduced identifiability of individual contributions."},
  {num:66,text:"The 'Just World Hypothesis' was proposed by:",A:"Fritz Heider",B:"Melvin Lerner",C:"Leon Festinger",D:"Stanley Milgram",ans:"B",exp:"Hypothesis — the belief that the world is fair and people get what they deserve. This can lead to victim-blaming, as people rationalize misfortunes as deserved to maintain their belief in a just world."},
  {num:67,text:"Which of the following is an example of the 'door-in-the-face' compliance technique?",A:"Asking for a small favor first, then a larger one",B:"Making a large, unreasonable request first, then a smaller target request",C:"Offering a free sample to induce reciprocity",D:"Using social proof to increase compliance",ans:"B",exp:"In the door-in-the-face technique, the requester starts with an extreme, unreasonable request (that will be refused), then follows with the smaller target request. Compliance increases due to reciprocal concession — the second request seems reasonable by comparison."},
  {num:68,text:"Deindividuation in crowds leads to:",A:"Increased self-awareness and reflection",B:"Reduced self-awareness and increased susceptibility to group norms and impulsive behavior",C:"Enhanced individual accountability",D:"Increased prosocial behavior",ans:"B",exp:"Deindividuation occurs in large groups or anonymous settings, causing a reduction in self-awareness and personal responsibility. This can lead to increased conformity to situational cues, disinhibition, and potentially antisocial behavior, as seen in crowd violence."},
  {num:69,text:"The tendency to attribute others' behavior to internal dispositions while underweighting situational factors is called:",A:"Actor-observer bias",B:"Fundamental Attribution Error",C:"Self-serving bias",D:"Hindsight bias",ans:"B",exp:"Error (FAE), described by Lee Ross, is the systematic tendency to over-attribute others' behavior to internal dispositional factors (personality, character) while underestimating the role of situational factors. This bias is reduced when we are the actor (actor-observer asymmetry)."},
  {num:70,text:"Henri Tajfel's Social Identity Theory proposes that:",A:"Self-esteem is primarily derived from personal achievements",B:"Individuals enhance self-esteem by positively evaluating the groups they belong to",C:"Social behavior is entirely determined by reinforcement history",D:"Prejudice arises solely from resource competition",ans:"B",exp:"Theory proposes that part of our self-concept derives from our group memberships. To maintain positive social identity, people favorably compare their in-group to out-groups, which can explain in-group favoritism and intergroup discrimination."},
  {num:71,text:"Aggression that is instrumental in nature is BEST described as:",A:"Reactive aggression triggered by frustration",B:"Aggression used as a means to achieve a goal",C:"Aggression resulting from provocation",D:"Impulsive aggression driven by anger",ans:"B",exp:"Instrumental aggression is premeditated, goal-directed behavior where aggression is a tool to achieve an objective (e.g., a thief using violence during a robbery). In contrast, reactive (hostile/affective) aggression is impulsive and driven by anger or frustration in response to a perceived provocation."},
  {num:72,text:"The 'bystander effect' states that an individual is LESS likely to offer help when:",A:"The emergency is clearly visible",B:"Other bystanders are present",C:"The victim is known to the bystander",D:"The emergency occurs in a familiar environment",ans:"B",exp:"Latané demonstrated that the presence of other bystanders reduces the likelihood that any individual will intervene in an emergency. This is attributed to diffusion of responsibility (someone else will help) and pluralistic ignorance (others are not reacting, so it may not be serious)."},
  {num:73,text:"In Piaget's theory, the ability to understand that the quantity of a substance remains unchanged when its shape is altered is called:",A:"Object permanence",B:"Conservation",C:"Egocentrism",D:"Centration",ans:"B",exp:"Conservation is the understanding that quantity (volume, mass, number) remains constant despite changes in physical appearance. This ability develops during the concrete operational stage (ages 7–11). Its absence (inability to conserve) is characteristic of the preoperational stage."},
  {num:74,text:"Mary Ainsworth's 'Strange Situation' procedure identified which attachment pattern as associated with inconsistent caregiving?",A:"Secure attachment",B:"Anxious-avoidant attachment",C:"Anxious-ambivalent (resistant) attachment",D:"Disorganized attachment",ans:"C",exp:"(c) Anxious-ambivalent (resistant) attachment Anxious-ambivalent (resistant) attachment is associated with inconsistent caregiving, where caregivers are sometimes responsive and sometimes not. Children show intense distress at separation, but are not easily comforted upon reunion, simultaneously seeking and resisting comfort."},
  {num:75,text:"According to Erikson, successfully resolving the 'Generativity vs. Stagnation' stage results in:",A:"A sense of personal meaning and life satisfaction",B:"Wisdom and ego integration",C:"Contribution to society and nurturing the next generation",D:"A stable sense of personal identity",ans:"C",exp:"Generativity vs. Stagnation stage (middle adulthood, ages 40–65) involves contributing to society, whether through raising children, mentoring others, or productive work. Successful resolution produces the virtue of 'care.' Failure leads to self-absorption and stagnation."},
  {num:76,text:"Vygotsky's concept of 'Zone of Proximal Development' (ZPD) refers to:",A:"The range of tasks a child can complete independently",B:"The gap between what a child can achieve alone and what they can achieve with guidance",C:"The optimal level of challenge that promotes cognitive development",D:"The sequence of cognitive stages from birth to adolescence",ans:"B",exp:"ZPD as the distance between a child's current independent problem-solving level and the potential level achievable with guidance from a more knowledgeable adult or peer. Scaffolding — temporary support within the ZPD — promotes development."},
  {num:77,text:"Kohlberg's 'post-conventional' level of moral development is characterized by:",A:"Obedience to authority to avoid punishment",B:"Conforming to social rules to maintain order",C:"Moral reasoning based on abstract principles, social contracts, and universal ethics",D:"Making moral decisions based on personal benefit",ans:"C",exp:"Kohlberg's post-conventional level (Stage 5: Social Contract; Stage 6: Universal Principles), moral reasoning is guided by abstract principles of justice and human rights that transcend any particular society's rules. This level is relatively rare and represents the highest moral reasoning."},
  {num:78,text:"The 'false belief task' (Wimmer & Perner's Sally-Anne test) is used to assess:",A:"Moral reasoning",B:"Concrete operational thinking",C:"Theory of mind",D:"Working memory capacity",ans:"C",exp:"Theory of mind (ToM) is the ability to attribute mental states (beliefs, intentions, desires) to others that differ from one's own. The Sally-Anne false belief task tests whether a child understands that others can hold beliefs that differ from reality. Children typically pass by age 4–5; this ability is impaired in ASD."},
  {num:79,text:"According to Bronfenbrenner's Ecological Systems Theory, the microsystem refers to:",A:"Interactions between the different settings the child inhabits",B:"Broader cultural and societal values",C:"The immediate environment in which the child directly participates",D:"Historical events affecting the developmental context",ans:"C",exp:"Bronfenbrenner's model, the microsystem is the innermost layer — the immediate setting where the child directly interacts (e.g., family, school, peers). The mesosystem involves connections between microsystems; the exosystem and macrosystem represent progressively broader contextual levels."},
  {num:80,text:"Object permanence — the understanding that objects continue to exist even when out of sight — develops primarily during Piaget's:",A:"Preoperational stage",B:"Sensorimotor stage",C:"Concrete operational stage",D:"Formal operational stage",ans:"B",exp:"Object permanence is one of the key cognitive achievements of the sensorimotor stage (0–2 years). Initially, infants act as though objects cease to exist when hidden (A-not-B error). By approximately 8–12 months, infants begin to search for hidden objects, demonstrating emerging object permanence."},
  {num:81,text:"The Thematic Apperception Test (TAT) is classified as a:",A:"Structured personality inventory",B:"Projective technique using ambiguous visual stimuli",C:"Neuropsychological assessment tool",D:"Behavioral rating scale",ans:"B",exp:"TAT (Murray & Morgan, 1943) is a projective technique where respondents create stories about ambiguous pictures. It is based on the assumption that people project their unconscious needs, motives, and conflicts onto the ambiguous stimuli, revealing underlying personality dynamics."},
  {num:82,text:"In the Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale (WAIS), the Processing Speed Index primarily measures:",A:"Verbal reasoning ability",B:"Spatial visualization",C:"Speed and accuracy of clerical and graphomotor tasks",D:"Abstract reasoning with novel information",ans:"C",exp:"Index (PSI) of the WAIS includes subtests like Symbol Search and Coding, which measure the speed and efficiency of basic cognitive and psychomotor processing. PSI is particularly sensitive to brain injury, ADHD, depression, and aging effects."},
  {num:83,text:"The L (Lie) scale on the MMPI-2 is designed to detect:",A:"Malingering of psychiatric symptoms",B:"Defensiveness and a tendency to present oneself in an unrealistically positive, virtuous manner",C:"Random responding or inconsistency",D:"Over-reporting of symptoms",ans:"B",exp:"MMPI-2 L (Lie) scale detects naive defensiveness — endorsement of unrealistically positive self-presentation items (e.g., 'I never get angry'). Elevated L scores suggest the respondent is presenting an idealized image, which may indicate distortion of clinical scale profiles."},
  {num:84,text:"Which of the following is a culturally adapted intelligence test developed and standardized in India?",A:"Stanford-Binet Intelligence Scales",B:"Wechsler Intelligence Scale for Children",C:"Binet-Kamat Test of Intelligence",D:"Cattell Culture Fair Intelligence Test",ans:"C",exp:"Test (BKT) was adapted and standardized in India by Dr. V. Kamat for use with Indian children. It is one of the most widely used indigenously standardized intelligence tests in India, particularly for assessing children in clinical and educational settings."},
  {num:85,text:"The Rorschach Inkblot Test scoring variable 'M' represents:",A:"The number of animal responses",B:"Human movement responses, indicative of empathy and inner fantasy life",C:"Color-dominated responses",D:"Texture responses related to interpersonal needs",ans:"B",exp:"Rorschach scoring, 'M' (Human Movement) refers to responses where the respondent perceives human figures in motion. Hermann Rorschach and subsequent theorists associated M responses with empathy, inner imaginative life, capacity for delay, and higher ego functioning."},
  {num:86,text:"The Beck Depression Inventory (BDI-II) is BEST described as:",A:"A clinician-administered structured diagnostic interview",B:"A self-report inventory measuring the cognitive and somatic symptoms of depression",C:"A projective test assessing underlying depressive dynamics",D:"A neuropsychological test sensitive to frontal lobe dysfunction",ans:"B",exp:"BDI-II (Beck et al., 1996) is a 21-item self-report questionnaire assessing the severity of depressive symptoms consistent with DSM-IV criteria. It measures both cognitive-affective (e.g., sadness, guilt) and somatic-vegetative (e.g., sleep, appetite) dimensions of depression."},
  {num:87,text:"Which of the following BEST describes the difference between reliability and validity in psychological testing?",A:"Reliability refers to accuracy; validity refers to precision",B:"A test can be valid without being reliable",C:"Reliability is necessary but not sufficient for validity",D:"Validity is a prerequisite for reliability",ans:"C",exp:"A test must be reliable (consistent) to be valid (accurate), but reliability alone does not ensure validity. A test can consistently measure something, but if it is not measuring what it claims to measure, it is reliable but not valid. Validity cannot exist without reliability, making reliability necessary but insufficient."},
  {num:88,text:"In classical test theory, the observed test score (X) is conceptualized as:",A:"X = True Score + Error Score",B:"X = True Score × Error Score",C:"X = True Score − Systematic Bias",D:"X = Error Score / Reliability",ans:"A",exp:"(a) X = True Score + Error Score Classical Test Theory (CTT) posits the fundamental equation: X = T + E (Observed Score = True Score + Error Score). The true score (T) reflects the 'real' ability, while error (E) represents random measurement error. Reliability is the ratio of true score variance to observed score variance."},
  {num:89,text:"In Alfred Adler's Individual Psychology, the concept of 'inferiority complex' refers to:",A:"The Oedipus complex applied to all individuals",B:"An overwhelming, paralysing sense of inadequacy that prevents striving toward superiority",C:"A healthy motivation to overcome personal weaknesses",D:"The unconscious sense of smallness compared to the father figure",ans:"B",exp:"Adler distinguished between normal feelings of inferiority (which motivate growth and compensation) and an inferiority complex (an overwhelming, generalized sense of inadequacy that impairs functioning). The complex develops when inferiority feelings are not adequately compensated, leading to avoidance rather than striving."},
  {num:90,text:"Raymond Cattell used factor analysis to identify 16 primary personality factors (16PF). He distinguished between 'surface traits' and 'source traits,' where source traits are:",A:"Observable behavioral expressions of personality",B:"Underlying, causative personality dimensions identified through factor analysis",C:"Traits that emerge only in social situations",D:"Temporary states rather than enduring dispositions",ans:"B",exp:"Cattell distinguished between surface traits (clusters of correlated behaviors visible in observation) and source traits (underlying, deeper personality dimensions identified through factor analysis). Source traits are the real structural units of personality and form the basis of the 16PF questionnaire."},
  {num:91,text:"Carl Rogers' concept of 'unconditional positive regard' in therapy involves:",A:"Accepting the client only when they demonstrate healthy behaviors",B:"Complete acceptance and non-judgmental prizing of the client regardless of what they say or do",C:"Reflecting the client's emotions back to them without interpretation",D:"Remaining emotionally neutral to maintain professional objectivity",ans:"B",exp:"Rogers' three core therapeutic conditions (with empathy and congruence). It involves the therapist's complete, non-judgmental acceptance of the client. It counters the 'conditions of worth' that Rogers believed cause psychological distress and incongruence."},
  {num:92,text:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'Barnum effect' (Forer effect) in personality assessment?",A:"The tendency to give socially desirable responses on personality tests",B:"The tendency to accept vague, general personality descriptions as uniquely applicable to oneself",C:"The statistical artifact whereby factor loadings appear higher than they are",D:"The halo effect inflating personality ratings",ans:"B",exp:"Barnum/Forer effect is the tendency for individuals to accept vague, general personality statements (e.g., horoscope-type descriptions) as highly specific and accurate self-descriptions. It poses a significant validity problem for unscientific personality assessments."},
  {num:93,text:"Hans Eysenck proposed that introverts, compared to extroverts, have:",A:"Lower baseline cortical arousal and therefore seek stimulation",B:"Higher baseline cortical arousal and therefore avoid additional stimulation",C:"More neurotic tendencies in all social situations",D:"Greater susceptibility to conditioning due to lower arousal thresholds",ans:"B",exp:"Eysenck's arousal theory proposes that introverts have higher baseline cortical arousal, causing them to be more sensitive to stimulation and therefore preferring quieter, less stimulating environments. Extroverts have lower arousal and seek external stimulation to reach an optimal level."},
  {num:94,text:"In Maslow's hierarchy, 'esteem needs' include all of the following EXCEPT:",A:"Achievement and competence",B:"Recognition from others",C:"Belonging and affection",D:"Self-respect",ans:"C",exp:"Esteem needs (the fourth level) include self-esteem (achievement, mastery, competence, self-respect) and esteem from others (recognition, status, prestige). Belonging and affection (love/belonging) constitute the third level, which must be satisfied before esteem needs become predominant."},
  {num:95,text:"Under the Mental Healthcare Act (MHCA) 2017, which of the following rights is explicitly guaranteed to persons with mental illness in India?",A:"Right to be detained indefinitely for treatment",B:"Right to access mental healthcare and treatment from the government",C:"Right to be treated only in private hospitals",D:"Right to refuse treatment under all circumstances",ans:"B",exp:"Act 2017 (India) guarantees several rights to persons with mental illness, including the right to access mental healthcare from the government, right to live in the community, right to confidentiality, and the right to make advance directives about treatment preferences."},
  {num:96,text:"The McNaughton Rules, used to determine criminal responsibility in India, establish that an accused is not responsible if, at the time of the offence:",A:"They were intoxicated by alcohol",B:"Due to mental disease, they did not know the nature of the act or that it was wrong",C:"They were under the influence of a personality disorder",D:"A psychiatrist testifies to the presence of any mental illness",ans:"B",exp:"Rules (1843), embedded in Section 84 of the Indian Penal Code, state that an accused is not criminally responsible if, at the time of the act, they were suffering from a disease of mind such that they did not know the nature and quality of the act, or did not know it was wrong."},
  {num:97,text:"The Rights of Persons with Disabilities (RPwD) Act 2016 in India defines disability to include mental illness. Which of the following is TRUE about this Act?",A:"It covers only physical disabilities",B:"It recognizes 21 specified disabilities including mental illness, autism, and intellectual disability",C:"It was enacted to replace the Persons with Disabilities Act 1995 and covers 7 disabilities",D:"It applies only to government employees",ans:"B",exp:"(b) It recognizes 21 specified disabilities including mental illness, autism, and intellectual disability The RPwD Act 2016 expanded the definition of disability from 7 (under the 1995 Act) to 21 specified categories, including mental illness, autism spectrum disorder, intellectual disability, and specific learning disabilities. It aims to ensure equal opportunities, protection of rights, and full participation."},
  {num:98,text:"Testamentary capacity requires that at the time of making a will, the person understands all EXCEPT:",A:"The nature and extent of their property",B:"The claims of those who might benefit",C:"The purpose and consequence of making a will",D:"The ability to predict future family conflicts",ans:"D",exp:"Testamentary capacity (legal ability to make a valid will) requires: (1) understanding the nature of a will, (2) knowing the nature and extent of property, (3) knowing the natural heirs (those who might reasonably benefit), and (4) understanding these facts simultaneously. The ability to predict future conflicts is not a requirement."},
  {num:99,text:"Which of the following BEST describes 'fitness to stand trial' in forensic psychology?",A:"Whether the accused committed the alleged offense",B:"Whether the accused was mentally ill at the time of the offense",C:"Whether the accused currently has sufficient mental capacity to understand the proceedings and assist in their own defense",D:"Whether the accused requires hospitalization rather than imprisonment",ans:"C",exp:"Fitness (or competency) to stand trial is a legal determination about the accused's current mental capacity — specifically, their ability to understand the nature and purpose of court proceedings and meaningfully assist counsel in their own defense. It is distinct from the insanity defense, which concerns mental state at the time of the offense."},
  {num:100,text:"Which organization in India is responsible for regulating the education and rehabilitation of persons with disabilities, including certifying clinical psychologists?",A:"Medical Council of India (MCI)",B:"Bar Council of India (BCI)",C:"Rehabilitation Council of India (RCI)",D:"Indian Council of Medical Research (ICMR)",ans:"C",exp:"The Rehabilitation Council of India (RCI), established under the RCI Act 1992, is the statutory body that regulates and standardizes training policies and programmes for rehabilitation professionals in India, including clinical psychologists, special educators, and other allied professionals. Mock Test 1 | Clinical Psychology Entrance Preparation | Page of"}
];

const TEST3_DATA = // Mock Test 3
[
  {num:1,text:"Which part of the brain is primarily responsible for regulating body temperature, hunger, thirst, and circadian rhythms?",A:"Thalamus",B:"Hypothalamus",C:"Amygdala",D:"Cerebellum",ans:"B",exp:"The hypothalamus is a small but crucial structure in the brain that regulates homeostatic functions including body temperature, hunger, thirst, sleep-wake cycles, and hormonal activity. It acts as the link between the nervous system and the endocrine system via the pituitary gland."},
  {num:2,text:"The neurotransmitter most directly implicated in Parkinson's disease is:",A:"Serotonin",B:"Acetylcholine",C:"Dopamine",D:"GABA",ans:"C",exp:"Parkinson's disease results primarily from the degeneration of dopaminergic neurons in the substantia nigra. Dopamine deficiency disrupts the smooth regulation of movement, leading to the hallmark symptoms of tremor, rigidity, and bradykinesia. Treatment typically involves dopamine replacement or receptor agonists."},
  {num:3,text:"Broca's area, critical for speech production, is located in the:",A:"Right temporal lobe",B:"Left parietal lobe",C:"Left frontal lobe",D:"Right occipital lobe",ans:"C",exp:"Broca's area is located in the left inferior frontal gyrus (Brodmann areas 44 and 45). Damage to this area results in Broca's (expressive) aphasia, characterised by halting, effortful speech with relatively preserved comprehension."},
  {num:4,text:"The split-brain research conducted by Sperry and Gazzaniga demonstrated that:",A:"Both hemispheres process language equally",B:"The right hemisphere controls speech production",C:"The two hemispheres can function independently after corpus callosum section",D:"The left hemisphere specialises in spatial tasks",ans:"C",exp:"Roger Sperry and Michael Gazzaniga's split-brain studies on patients who had undergone corpus callosotomy showed that each hemisphere processes information independently. The left hemisphere typically handles language while the right hemisphere excels at visuospatial tasks. These findings earned Sperry the 1981 Nobel Prize in Physiology."},
  {num:5,text:"Which of the following neurotransmitters is primarily associated with the regulation of mood, appetite, and sleep, and is targeted by SSRIs?",A:"Norepinephrine",B:"Dopamine",C:"Serotonin",D:"Glutamate",ans:"C",exp:"Serotonin (5-hydroxytryptamine) plays a key role in mood regulation, appetite, sleep, and social behaviour. Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) block the reuptake of serotonin, increasing its availability in the synapse and are first-line treatments for depression and anxiety disorders."},
  {num:6,text:"The gate control theory of pain was proposed by:",A:"Ronald Melzack and Patrick Wall",B:"Ivan Pavlov and John Watson",C:"Charles Sherrington and Edgar Adrian",D:"Henry Head and Gordon Holmes",ans:"A",exp:"Ronald Melzack and Patrick Wall proposed the gate control theory in 1965. The theory posits that a 'gate' mechanism in the spinal cord (specifically in the dorsal horn) can modulate the perception of pain by controlling the flow of nerve impulses from peripheral fibres to the brain."},
  {num:7,text:"An individual sustains damage to the cerebellum. Which of the following deficits would MOST likely be observed?",A:"Loss of short-term memory",B:"Impaired coordination and balance",C:"Personality changes and impulsivity",D:"Loss of language comprehension",ans:"B",exp:"The cerebellum (meaning 'little brain') coordinates voluntary movements, balance, and fine motor control. Cerebellar lesions lead to ataxia (uncoordinated movements), dysmetria (misjudging distances), and tremors. The cerebellum does not play a direct role in personality or language processing."},
  {num:8,text:"Which of the following describes the function of myelin sheath in neurons?",A:"It transmits sensory information to the thalamus",B:"It speeds up the conduction of nerve impulses along the axon",C:"It synthesises neurotransmitters in the cell body",D:"It forms synaptic connections between neurons",ans:"B",exp:"The myelin sheath is a fatty insulating layer that wraps around the axon of a neuron. It facilitates saltatory conduction — the nerve impulse jumps between nodes of Ranvier, greatly increasing the speed of signal transmission. Demyelination, as in multiple sclerosis, severely disrupts neural communication."},
  {num:9,text:"In the autonomic nervous system, the sympathetic division is primarily responsible for:",A:"Stimulating digestion and conserving energy",B:"Increasing heart rate and mobilising energy for 'fight or flight'",C:"Constricting the pupils in bright light",D:"Reducing breathing rate during sleep",ans:"B",exp:"'fight or flight' The sympathetic nervous system activates the fight-or-flight response: it increases heart rate, dilates pupils, inhibits digestion, and mobilises energy resources. This prepares the organism for rapid action in response to perceived threats. The parasympathetic system has opposing 'rest and digest' effects."},
  {num:10,text:"Kluver-Bucy syndrome, resulting from bilateral temporal lobe damage, typically includes all of the following EXCEPT:",A:"Hypersexuality",B:"Hyperorality",C:"Placidity and loss of fear",D:"Hyperaggression and rage",ans:"D",exp:"Kluver-Bucy syndrome follows bilateral removal or damage of the temporal lobes, including the amygdala. Features include placidity, visual agnosia, hyperorality (putting objects in the mouth), hypersexuality, and dietary changes. Hyperaggression is NOT a feature — rather, affected individuals show an absence of normal fear and aggression."},
  {num:11,text:"Which of the following is the MOST accurate description of a synapse?",A:"A type of glial cell that insulates the axon",B:"The junction between two neurons where chemical signals are transmitted",C:"The initial segment of the axon where action potentials are generated",D:"The region of the dendrite that receives electrical impulses directly",ans:"B",exp:"A synapse is the specialised junction between two neurons (or a neuron and a target cell) across which neurotransmitters carry signals. It consists of the presynaptic terminal, the synaptic cleft, and the postsynaptic membrane with receptors. Chemical synapses allow directional communication across the nervous system."},
  {num:12,text:"The 'pleasure centre' of the brain, identified through early self-stimulation studies by Olds and Milner, is primarily associated with which region?",A:"Prefrontal cortex",B:"Septal area and medial forebrain bundle",C:"Hippocampus",D:"Pons",ans:"B",exp:"James Olds and Peter Milner (1954) discovered that rats would repeatedly self-stimulate electrodes implanted in the septal area and medial forebrain bundle. This circuit, heavily mediated by dopamine, is now understood as the brain's reward pathway and underlies motivation, pleasure, and addictive behaviour."},
  {num:13,text:"According to DSM-5, a diagnosis of Major Depressive Disorder requires the presence of depressive symptoms for at least:",A:"1 week",B:"2 weeks",C:"1 month",D:"6 months",ans:"B",exp:"DSM-5 requires that at least five depressive symptoms be present during the same 2-week period, with at least one symptom being either depressed mood or loss of interest/pleasure (anhedonia). Symptoms must cause significant impairment in daily functioning."},
  {num:14,text:"Which of the following is a NEGATIVE symptom of schizophrenia?",A:"Auditory hallucinations",B:"Grandiose delusions",C:"Flat affect",D:"Disorganised speech",ans:"C",exp:"Negative symptoms in schizophrenia refer to diminished or absent normal functions. Flat affect (reduced emotional expression) is a classic negative symptom, along with alogia (poverty of speech), avolition, and anhedonia. Hallucinations, delusions, and disorganised speech are positive symptoms (additions to normal function)."},
  {num:15,text:"Persistent depressive disorder (dysthymia) in DSM-5 requires a depressed mood for most of the day, for more days than not, for at least:",A:"6 months",B:"1 year",C:"2 years",D:"5 years",ans:"C",exp:"Persistent Depressive Disorder (previously called dysthymia) requires chronically depressed mood for at least 2 years in adults (1 year in children and adolescents). Though less severe than MDD, its chronic nature significantly impairs quality of life and functioning."},
  {num:16,text:"A patient experiences recurrent, unexpected panic attacks and persistent worry about future attacks for over a month. The MOST likely diagnosis is:",A:"Generalised Anxiety Disorder",B:"Social Anxiety Disorder",C:"Panic Disorder",D:"Agoraphobia",ans:"C",exp:"Panic Disorder is diagnosed when recurrent unexpected panic attacks are followed by at least one month of persistent concern about future attacks, or significant maladaptive behavioural change. The attacks are 'unexpected' — not tied to a specific trigger — distinguishing it from specific phobia or social anxiety disorder."},
  {num:17,text:"The MMSE (Mini-Mental State Examination) is primarily used to screen for:",A:"Personality disorders",B:"Psychotic symptoms",C:"Cognitive impairment and dementia",D:"Substance use disorders",ans:"C",exp:"The MMSE, developed by Folstein et al. (1975), is a widely used 30-point questionnaire assessing orientation, registration, attention, recall, and language. Scores below 24 suggest cognitive impairment; it is used to screen for dementia and monitor disease progression or treatment response."},
  {num:18,text:"Which of the following is considered a dissociative disorder in DSM-5?",A:"Conversion disorder",B:"Depersonalisation/Derealisation disorder",C:"Somatic symptom disorder",D:"Illness anxiety disorder",ans:"B",exp:"Depersonalisation/Derealisation Disorder (DDD) is classified under dissociative disorders in DSM-5. It involves persistent feelings of detachment from one's mental processes or body (depersonalisation) or surroundings (derealisation). Conversion disorder is now under somatic symptom and related disorders."},
  {num:19,text:"Korsakoff's syndrome is primarily associated with deficiency of:",A:"Vitamin B12 (Cobalamin)",B:"Vitamin B1 (Thiamine)",C:"Vitamin D",D:"Folate",ans:"B",exp:"Korsakoff's syndrome results from thiamine (Vitamin B1) deficiency, typically associated with chronic alcohol use. It is characterised by severe anterograde amnesia, retrograde amnesia, and confabulation (fabrication of memories to fill gaps). It often follows Wernicke's encephalopathy in Wernicke-Korsakoff syndrome."},
  {num:20,text:"In which personality disorder is identity disturbance, impulsivity, intense unstable relationships, and recurrent suicidal behaviour most characteristic?",A:"Narcissistic Personality Disorder",B:"Antisocial Personality Disorder",C:"Histrionic Personality Disorder",D:"Borderline Personality Disorder",ans:"D",exp:"Borderline Personality Disorder (BPD) is characterised by pervasive instability in interpersonal relationships, self-image, and affect, along with marked impulsivity. Identity disturbance (unstable sense of self), fear of abandonment, recurrent self-harm, and intense, unstable relationships are core features. DBT is the evidence-based treatment."},
  {num:21,text:"Thought insertion, thought broadcasting, and passivity experiences are MOST characteristic of:",A:"Bipolar I Disorder",B:"Borderline Personality Disorder",C:"Schizophrenia",D:"OCD",ans:"C",exp:"Thought insertion (belief that thoughts are placed in one's mind by an external force), thought broadcasting (belief that one's thoughts are being transmitted to others), and passivity experiences (body or actions controlled by external forces) are Schneider's first-rank symptoms, historically considered highly characteristic of schizophrenia."},
  {num:22,text:"Which of the following is NOT a criterion for Posttraumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD) according to DSM-5?",A:"Intrusive memories or flashbacks",B:"Avoidance of trauma-related stimuli",C:"Marked euphoria and grandiosity",D:"Negative alterations in cognitions and mood",ans:"C",exp:"DSM-5 PTSD criteria include intrusion symptoms, avoidance, negative alterations in cognitions/mood, and alterations in arousal/reactivity — all persisting for more than one month. Euphoria and grandiosity are NOT features of PTSD; they are more consistent with mania in Bipolar Disorder."},
  {num:23,text:"Body Dysmorphic Disorder (BDD) is classified under which category in DSM-5?",A:"Somatic Symptom and Related Disorders",B:"Anxiety Disorders",C:"Obsessive-Compulsive and Related Disorders",D:"Trauma and Stressor-Related Disorders",ans:"C",exp:"DSM-5 classifies BDD under Obsessive-Compulsive and Related Disorders. It involves preoccupation with perceived flaws in physical appearance, repetitive behaviours (e.g., mirror checking, grooming), and significant distress or functional impairment. It shares features with OCD including intrusive thoughts and compulsive behaviours."},
  {num:24,text:"Capgras syndrome, in which a person believes that a close relative has been replaced by an imposter, is a type of:",A:"Delusional disorder",B:"Dissociative identity disorder",C:"Folie à deux",D:"Ganser syndrome",ans:"A",exp:"Capgras syndrome is a delusional misidentification syndrome, categorised under delusional disorder. The person recognises familiar faces but believes they are impostors. It may occur in schizophrenia, dementia, or after traumatic brain injury. It is thought to result from disconnection between face recognition and emotional familiarity circuits."},
  {num:25,text:"The learned helplessness theory of depression was proposed by:",A:"Aaron Beck",B:"Albert Ellis",C:"Martin Seligman",D:"David Clark",ans:"C",exp:"Martin Seligman proposed learned helplessness theory based on animal studies where dogs given inescapable shocks later failed to escape avoidable shocks. He extrapolated this to human depression, arguing that perceived uncontrollability leads to passive, helpless behaviour. He later revised this into the reformulated attributional model with Abramson et al."},
  {num:26,text:"Which of the following is a defining feature that differentiates OCD from OCPD (Obsessive-Compulsive Personality Disorder)?",A:"Presence of ego-dystonic intrusive thoughts and compulsions in OCD",B:"Both involve perfectionism that is ego-syntonic",C:"OCPD has more severe functional impairment than OCD",D:"OCD is classified under personality disorders in DSM-5",ans:"A",exp:"OCD is characterised by ego-dystonic obsessions (unwanted, intrusive thoughts experienced as distressing and alien to the self) and compulsions (repetitive behaviours performed to reduce anxiety). OCPD involves ego-syntonic perfectionism and rigidity — traits the individual sees as part of their identity, not as a problem."},
  {num:27,text:"Waxy flexibility and mutism are symptoms most associated with which subtype of schizophrenia (as per older DSM-IV classification)?",A:"Paranoid schizophrenia",B:"Disorganised schizophrenia",C:"Catatonic schizophrenia",D:"Residual schizophrenia",ans:"C",exp:"Catatonic schizophrenia (retained in ICD-10 though removed as a subtype in DSM-5) is characterised by psychomotor disturbances including waxy flexibility (limbs remain in positions placed by others), stupor, mutism, negativism, and posturing. DSM-5 now treats catatonia as a specifier applicable to multiple disorders."},
  {num:28,text:"The term 'anhedonia' refers to:",A:"An inability to feel pleasure or interest in previously enjoyed activities",B:"Excessive and uncontrollable laughter or crying",C:"Persistent and pervasive worry about multiple life domains",D:"A pathological fear of being alone",ans:"A",exp:"Anhedonia is defined as the diminished ability to experience pleasure or interest in activities that were previously enjoyable. It is a core symptom of Major Depressive Disorder and can also occur in schizophrenia, substance use disorders, and other conditions. It reflects a disruption in the brain's reward system."},
  {num:29,text:"In DSM-5, Intellectual Disability (Intellectual Developmental Disorder) is primarily defined by:",A:"An IQ score below 70 alone",B:"Deficits in intellectual AND adaptive functioning, with onset during the developmental period",C:"Inability to attend mainstream school",D:"Presence of a chromosomal abnormality",ans:"B",exp:"DSM-5 defines Intellectual Disability by three criteria: deficits in intellectual functioning (reasoning, problem solving, learning), deficits in adaptive behaviour (conceptual, social, and practical domains), and onset during the developmental period. An IQ score alone is insufficient; adaptive functioning deficits must also be present."},
  {num:30,text:"Which of the following best describes the 'double-bind' hypothesis proposed by Gregory Bateson in relation to schizophrenia?",A:"Schizophrenia arises from a double genetic vulnerability from both parents",B:"Contradictory messages from caregivers create a no-win communicative trap that may contribute to schizophrenia",C:"The disorder involves two distinct phases: prodromal and active",D:"Schizophrenia results from both biological and psychosocial stressors acting simultaneously",ans:"B",exp:"Gregory Bateson (1956) proposed that conflicting or contradictory messages — particularly from parents — where no response is correct ('double-bind'), contribute to the development of schizophrenia. Although largely unsupported as a primary cause today, it was an influential concept in family systems therapy and communication theory."},
  {num:31,text:"The Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale (WAIS) yields which of the following primary index scores in its current edition?",A:"Verbal IQ, Performance IQ, and Full Scale IQ only",B:"Verbal Comprehension, Perceptual Reasoning, Working Memory, and Processing Speed Indices",C:"Crystallised Intelligence, Fluid Intelligence, and Memory Quotient",D:"General Factor (g), Specific Factors (s), and Group Factors",ans:"B",exp:"The WAIS-IV (and WAIS-V in its updated form) yields four primary index scores: Verbal Comprehension Index (VCI), Perceptual Reasoning Index (PRI), Working Memory Index (WMI), and Processing Speed Index (PSI), plus a Full Scale IQ. The older WAIS editions used Verbal IQ and Performance IQ, which were removed in WAIS-IV."},
  {num:32,text:"The Thematic Apperception Test (TAT) was developed by:",A:"Hermann Rorschach",B:"Henry Murray and Christiana Morgan",C:"David Wechsler",D:"Raymond Cattell",ans:"B",exp:"The TAT was developed by Henry Murray and Christiana Morgan at Harvard in 1935. It is a projective test in which individuals tell stories about ambiguous pictures; the narratives are thought to reflect underlying motivations, conflicts, and personality. It is widely used in clinical and research settings despite variable psychometric properties."},
  {num:33,text:"In psychometric theory, reliability refers to:",A:"The extent to which a test measures what it claims to measure",B:"The consistency or stability of test scores across repeated administrations",C:"The degree to which test scores predict a relevant criterion",D:"The extent to which a test covers the content domain of interest",ans:"B",exp:"Reliability refers to the consistency and stability of measurement. A reliable test produces similar scores under the same conditions over time (test-retest reliability), across different items measuring the same construct (internal consistency), or across different raters (inter-rater reliability). Reliability is a necessary but not sufficient condition for validity."},
  {num:34,text:"The Minnesota Multiphasic Personality Inventory (MMPI-2) contains validity scales to detect:",A:"Intelligence level and cognitive functioning",B:"Response styles such as faking good, faking bad, or random responding",C:"Neurological deficits and brain damage",D:"Aptitude and occupational suitability",ans:"B",exp:"The MMPI-2 includes validity scales (e.g., L — Lie, F — Infrequency, K — Correction, VRIN, TRIN) that assess the individual's test-taking approach. These detect over-reporting (faking bad/malingering), under-reporting (faking good/defensive responding), inconsistent responding, and other response biases that affect the interpretability of clinical scales."},
  {num:35,text:"A test has high reliability but low validity. Which of the following statements BEST describes this situation?",A:"The test consistently measures something, but not necessarily what it claims to measure",B:"The test measures the right construct but with inconsistent results",C:"High reliability automatically guarantees high validity",D:"Such a situation is logically impossible",ans:"A",exp:"A test can be highly reliable (consistent) yet invalid (not measuring the intended construct). For example, a scale consistently measuring weight could not validly measure intelligence. Reliability is necessary but not sufficient for validity. Validity always implies some degree of reliability, but reliability does not imply validity."},
  {num:36,text:"The Bender-Gestalt Test is primarily used to assess:",A:"Verbal intelligence and vocabulary",B:"Visuo-motor integration and organicity",C:"Personality through story-telling",D:"Achievement and academic skills",ans:"B",exp:"The Bender Visual-Motor Gestalt Test (Bender-Gestalt) requires individuals to copy geometric designs. It is used to screen for visuo-motor integration difficulties, neurological impairment (organicity), and developmental delays. The Koppitz scoring system is widely used for children; the BVMGT-II is the current edition."},
  {num:37,text:"In the Rorschach Inkblot Test, the 'F+%' (good form percentage) is an index of:",A:"Emotional responsiveness",B:"Reality testing and perceptual accuracy",C:"Creativity and originality",D:"Level of anxiety",ans:"B",exp:"In Rorschach scoring, the F+% (percentage of good form responses) measures the degree to which a person's perceptions match what is conventionally seen in the blots. High F+% suggests intact reality testing and perceptual accuracy; low F+% may indicate impaired reality testing, which is associated with psychotic disorders."},
  {num:38,text:"Factor analysis of intelligence led Raymond Cattell to propose which distinction?",A:"Verbal vs. performance intelligence",B:"Crystallised intelligence (Gc) vs. fluid intelligence (Gf)",C:"Primary mental abilities vs. secondary mental abilities",D:"General intelligence (g) vs. specific factors (s)",ans:"B",exp:"Raymond Cattell distinguished between fluid intelligence (Gf) — the ability to think and reason abstractly, solve novel problems, and adapt to new situations — and crystallised intelligence (Gc) — accumulated knowledge and skills acquired through experience and education. Gf tends to decline with age; Gc tends to be maintained or even increase across the lifespan."},
  {num:39,text:"Which of the following best describes construct validity?",A:"The degree to which a test covers the full content domain",B:"The degree to which a test measures the theoretical construct it is designed to measure",C:"The ability of the test to predict future performance",D:"The consistency of scores across different test administrations",ans:"B",exp:"Construct validity refers to how well a test measures the underlying theoretical construct it is supposed to assess (e.g., anxiety, intelligence, empathy). Evidence for construct validity is accumulated through convergent validity (correlating with related measures), discriminant validity (not correlating with unrelated measures), and factor analysis."},
  {num:40,text:"The House-Tree-Person (HTP) technique is classified as which type of assessment tool?",A:"Objective personality test",B:"Neuropsychological battery",C:"Projective technique",D:"Achievement test",ans:"C",exp:"The House-Tree-Person (HTP) test, developed by John Buck, is a projective drawing technique. Individuals draw a house, a tree, and a person, and the drawings are interpreted to reveal personality characteristics, emotional functioning, and interpersonal styles. Like other projective tests, its reliability and validity are debated in the literature."},
  {num:41,text:"Which therapeutic approach uses the ABC model (Activating event, Beliefs, Consequences) as its central framework?",A:"Person-Centred Therapy",B:"Dialectical Behaviour Therapy",C:"Rational Emotive Behaviour Therapy (REBT)",D:"Acceptance and Commitment Therapy (ACT)",ans:"C",exp:"REBT, developed by Albert Ellis, uses the ABC (and later ABCDE) model: Activating event → Beliefs (rational or irrational) → Consequences (emotional/behavioural). The D stands for Disputing irrational beliefs, and E for the new Effect. REBT holds that it is not the event itself but one's beliefs about it that cause distress."},
  {num:42,text:"Systematic desensitisation, developed by Joseph Wolpe, is based on the principle of:",A:"Operant conditioning and token economies",B:"Reciprocal inhibition — the pairing of anxiety with deep relaxation",C:"Unconditional positive regard and empathic understanding",D:"Insight into unconscious conflicts through interpretation",ans:"B",exp:"Systematic desensitisation pairs anxiety-provoking stimuli with a relaxation response, based on Wolpe's principle of reciprocal inhibition — the idea that anxiety and relaxation cannot coexist simultaneously. The client is progressively exposed (in imagination or in vivo) to stimuli from a fear hierarchy while maintaining relaxation."},
  {num:43,text:"In Dialectical Behaviour Therapy (DBT), the four modules of skills training are:",A:"Cognitive restructuring, relaxation, problem-solving, social skills",B:"Mindfulness, distress tolerance, emotion regulation, and interpersonal effectiveness",C:"Exposure, response prevention, cognitive challenging, and behavioural activation",D:"Free association, dream analysis, transference interpretation, and working through",ans:"B",exp:"DBT, developed by Marsha Linehan, includes four skills training modules: (1) Mindfulness (core skill), (2) Distress Tolerance (crisis survival skills), (3) Emotion Regulation (changing unwanted emotions), and (4) Interpersonal Effectiveness (navigating relationships). DBT was originally developed for Borderline Personality Disorder."},
  {num:44,text:"The concept of 'unconditional positive regard' is central to which therapeutic approach?",A:"Psychoanalysis",B:"Gestalt Therapy",C:"Person-Centred (Rogerian) Therapy",D:"Cognitive Behaviour Therapy",ans:"C",exp:"Carl Rogers identified three core conditions in Person-Centred Therapy: unconditional positive regard (accepting the client without judgment), empathy (accurately understanding the client's inner world), and congruence (genuineness or authenticity of the therapist). Together, these create a therapeutic climate that facilitates self-actualisation."},
  {num:45,text:"Eye Movement Desensitisation and Reprocessing (EMDR) therapy was developed by:",A:"Francine Shapiro",B:"Aaron Beck",C:"Peter Levine",D:"Bessel van der Kolk",ans:"A",exp:"EMDR was developed by Francine Shapiro in 1987. It involves the client recalling traumatic memories while performing bilateral eye movements (or other bilateral stimulation). EMDR is classified as an evidence-based treatment for PTSD by the WHO, APA, and other bodies. Its mechanism of action is debated but may involve reducing the vividness and emotional charge of traumatic memories."},
  {num:46,text:"In psychoanalysis, the process by which the patient transfers feelings, attitudes, and expectations from past relationships onto the therapist is called:",A:"Countertransference",B:"Projection",C:"Transference",D:"Resistance",ans:"C",exp:"Transference is a central concept in psychoanalytic therapy, first described by Freud. The client unconsciously redirects feelings and desires from past significant relationships (typically parental) onto the therapist. Analysing transference allows insight into the client's relational patterns. Countertransference refers to the therapist's emotional reactions to the client."},
  {num:47,text:"Motivational Interviewing (MI), developed by Miller and Rollnick, is MOST aligned with which therapeutic principle?",A:"Confrontation and challenging the client's denials about their problem",B:"Eliciting intrinsic motivation for change through a collaborative, empathic style",C:"Providing psychoeducation and skills training in a structured format",D:"Identifying and modifying cognitive distortions through Socratic questioning",ans:"B",exp:"Motivational Interviewing (MI), developed by William Miller and Stephen Rollnick, is a collaborative, person-centred approach designed to elicit and strengthen a person's own motivation for change. It uses techniques like reflective listening, affirmation, summarising, and evoking change talk, avoiding confrontation and utilising the client's ambivalence constructively."},
  {num:48,text:"Exposure and Response Prevention (ERP) is the behavioural treatment of choice for:",A:"Social Anxiety Disorder",B:"Panic Disorder",C:"Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (OCD)",D:"Specific Phobia",ans:"C",exp:"ERP is the gold standard behavioural treatment for OCD, with strong empirical support. It involves exposing the client to feared obsessional triggers (exposure) while refraining from compulsive rituals (response prevention). This breaks the anxiety-reduction cycle maintained by compulsions and leads to habituation and extinction of the obsessional fear."},
  {num:49,text:"The therapeutic technique of 'empty chair' is associated with which therapeutic approach?",A:"Cognitive Behaviour Therapy",B:"Gestalt Therapy",C:"Psychoanalysis",D:"Adlerian Therapy",ans:"B",exp:"The 'empty chair' technique is a hallmark of Gestalt Therapy, developed by Fritz Perls. The client speaks to an imaginary person (or a part of themselves) in an empty chair, facilitating emotional expression, conflict resolution, and increased self-awareness. It helps clients work through unfinished business and conflicting aspects of their personality."},
  {num:50,text:"Acceptance and Commitment Therapy (ACT) is based primarily on which theoretical framework?",A:"Classical conditioning and stimulus control",B:"Relational Frame Theory and psychological flexibility",C:"Schema theory and core beliefs",D:"Object relations and attachment theory",ans:"B",exp:"ACT, developed by Steven Hayes, is grounded in Relational Frame Theory (RFT) — a behaviour-analytic account of language and cognition. ACT aims to increase psychological flexibility through six core processes: acceptance, defusion, present-moment awareness, self-as-context, values clarification, and committed action. Unlike CBT, it targets relationship with thoughts rather than their content."},
  {num:51,text:"Aversion therapy is MOST ethically controversial because:",A:"It relies solely on verbal instruction with no behavioural component",B:"It intentionally pairs undesired behaviour with an unpleasant stimulus, raising consent and harm concerns",C:"It requires a long-term therapeutic relationship and is time-consuming",D:"It ignores the client's cognitive processes",ans:"B",exp:"Aversion therapy pairs an unwanted behaviour (e.g., substance use) with an aversive stimulus (e.g., nausea-inducing drug or mild electric shock) to reduce its frequency. Ethical concerns centre on the use of intentional pain/discomfort, issues of informed consent, potential for misuse, and questions about its efficacy compared to less aversive alternatives."},
  {num:52,text:"Which of the following is a core technique in Cognitive Behaviour Therapy (CBT) for depression?",A:"Free association and dream interpretation",B:"Behavioural activation and activity scheduling",C:"Paradoxical intention and deflection",D:"Systematic desensitisation hierarchy construction",ans:"B",exp:"Behavioural activation is a core CBT technique for depression that targets withdrawal and inactivity — maintaining factors in depression. By scheduling and engaging in activities that previously brought pleasure or a sense of mastery, clients break the cycle of avoidance and low mood. It has strong evidence as both a standalone and component of CBT."},
  {num:53,text:"Lev Vygotsky's concept of the 'Zone of Proximal Development' (ZPD) refers to:",A:"The stage at which a child develops object permanence",B:"The range between what a child can achieve independently and what they can achieve with guidance",C:"The age range during which language acquisition is most sensitive",D:"The developmental gap between concrete and formal operational thinking",ans:"B",exp:"Vygotsky's ZPD is the distance between a child's actual developmental level (what they can do independently) and the level of potential development (what they can do with scaffolding from a more capable peer or adult). This concept emphasises the social and interactive nature of learning and has had profound impact on educational psychology."},
  {num:54,text:"According to Erikson's theory, the psychosocial crisis of 'Intimacy vs. Isolation' is characteristic of:",A:"Adolescence (12–18 years)",B:"Early adulthood (20s–30s)",C:"Middle adulthood (40s–60s)",D:"Late adulthood (60+ years)",ans:"B",exp:"Erikson's stage of Intimacy vs. Isolation occurs in early adulthood (roughly 20s–30s). The key task is forming close, committed relationships. Success leads to the virtue of love; failure results in isolation and loneliness. This stage follows Identity vs. Role Confusion, where the individual must have established a stable sense of identity first."},
  {num:55,text:"In Piaget's theory, the ability to understand that quantity remains constant despite changes in shape or appearance (e.g., pouring liquid) is called:",A:"Object permanence",B:"Egocentrism",C:"Conservation",D:"Seriation",ans:"C",exp:"Conservation is the understanding that certain properties (number, volume, mass) remain constant despite changes in appearance. Piaget believed children develop conservation during the concrete operational stage (approximately 7–11 years). Before this, children in the preoperational stage are misled by appearances (centration) and lack reversibility in thinking."},
  {num:56,text:"Mary Ainsworth's Strange Situation procedure identified which attachment patterns in infants?",A:"Secure, fearful, dismissive, and preoccupied",B:"Secure, anxious-ambivalent, and avoidant (and later disorganised)",C:"Type A, Type B, Type C, and Type D in order of security",D:"Attachment, detachment, re-attachment, and autonomy",ans:"B",exp:"Ainsworth's Strange Situation (1970) identified three main patterns: secure attachment (uses caregiver as secure base), anxious-ambivalent/resistant attachment (distressed, not easily comforted on reunion), and avoidant attachment (minimal distress, avoids caregiver). Main and Solomon later added disorganised/disoriented attachment, associated with frightening or frightened caregiving."},
  {num:57,text:"Lawrence Kohlberg's highest level of moral reasoning is the:",A:"Preconventional level — punishment and obedience",B:"Conventional level — social order and law",C:"Postconventional level — social contract and universal ethical principles",D:"Superconventional level — transcendence and altruism",ans:"C",exp:"Kohlberg's model has three levels: Preconventional (self-interest, avoiding punishment), Conventional (maintaining social norms and laws), and Postconventional (abstract principles of justice and human rights). Stage 6 of the postconventional level involves universal ethical principles that transcend particular laws, though Kohlberg acknowledged few people consistently reach this stage."},
  {num:58,text:"The concept of 'object permanence' — the understanding that objects continue to exist even when not visible — is achieved during Piaget's:",A:"Preoperational stage",B:"Concrete operational stage",C:"Formal operational stage",D:"Sensorimotor stage",ans:"D",exp:"Object permanence typically develops between 8 and 12 months during Piaget's sensorimotor stage (birth to approximately 2 years). Before this milestone, infants act as though objects that disappear no longer exist. Object permanence is considered a foundational cognitive achievement and is related to the development of representational thought."},
  {num:59,text:"Harry Harlow's contact comfort studies with infant rhesus monkeys demonstrated that:",A:"Attachment is primarily driven by the provision of food (cupboard love)",B:"Infants preferred the cloth-covered surrogate mother, suggesting warmth/comfort drives attachment",C:"Monkeys form attachment only after 6 months of age",D:"Social play is more important than contact comfort in development",ans:"B",exp:"Harlow's studies showed that infant monkeys separated from their mothers spent significantly more time clinging to a soft cloth surrogate even when milk was only available from a wire surrogate. This challenged drive-reduction theories of attachment (that infants attach to whoever feeds them) and supported the primacy of comfort and security in attachment formation."},
  {num:60,text:"Diana Baumrind identified three primary parenting styles. Which of the following best describes 'authoritative' parenting?",A:"High demands, low responsiveness — parents set strict rules without warmth",B:"High responsiveness, low demands — parents are permissive and child-led",C:"High demands AND high responsiveness — parents set clear expectations with warmth and explanation",D:"Low demands, low responsiveness — parents are largely uninvolved",ans:"C",exp:"Authoritative parenting (Baumrind, 1966) combines high demandingness (clear expectations, consistent discipline) with high responsiveness (warmth, sensitivity, open communication). Research consistently shows that children raised with authoritative parenting show better academic achievement, higher self-esteem, and fewer behavioural problems compared to other styles."},
  {num:61,text:"The concept of 'theory of mind' refers to the ability to:",A:"Understand abstract scientific theories in adolescence",B:"Attribute mental states (beliefs, desires, intentions) to oneself and others",C:"Form logical hypotheses and test them systematically",D:"Understand cause-and-effect relationships in the physical world",ans:"B",exp:"Theory of Mind (ToM) is the capacity to understand that others have mental states — beliefs, desires, intentions — that may differ from one's own and from reality. It is typically assessed using false-belief tasks (e.g., Sally-Anne task) and develops around age 4. Deficits in ToM are a hallmark of Autism Spectrum Disorder."},
  {num:62,text:"In the context of adolescent development, James Marcia's concept of 'identity foreclosure' describes an adolescent who has:",A:"Committed to an identity after thorough exploration",B:"Made a commitment to an identity without exploration, often adopting parents' values",C:"Neither explored nor committed to any identity",D:"Abandoned a previous identity and is actively exploring new options",ans:"B",exp:"' values James Marcia described four identity statuses: identity diffusion (no exploration, no commitment), foreclosure (commitment without exploration — often parental values adopted wholesale), moratorium (active exploration, no commitment yet), and identity achievement (commitment after exploration). Foreclosure may appear adaptive but lacks the autonomy that comes from genuine exploration."},
  {num:63,text:"Atkinson and Shiffrin's multi-store model of memory proposed the following sequence of memory stores:",A:"Long-term memory → short-term memory → sensory memory",B:"Sensory memory → short-term memory → long-term memory",C:"Working memory → episodic buffer → phonological loop",D:"Procedural → semantic → episodic memory",ans:"B",exp:"The Multi-Store Model (1968) by Atkinson and Shiffrin proposed that information flows from sensory memory (very brief, high capacity), through short-term memory (limited capacity: ~7±2 chunks, ~18-30 seconds), and into long-term memory (unlimited capacity, permanent). Rehearsal in STM transfers information to LTM."},
  {num:64,text:"The 'levels of processing' framework proposed by Craik and Lockhart (1972) suggests that memory retention depends on:",A:"The number of times information is rehearsed (maintenance rehearsal)",B:"The depth at which information is processed — deeper (semantic) processing leads to better retention",C:"The speed of encoding and the type of storage used",D:"The emotional valence of the information at the time of encoding",ans:"B",exp:"Craik and Lockhart proposed that memory trace durability depends on the depth of processing: shallow (structural/phonemic) processing leads to poor retention, while deep (semantic) processing — involving meaning — produces more durable memory traces. This challenged the multi-store model by emphasising quality, not just repetition, of processing."},
  {num:65,text:"The 'cocktail party effect' refers to:",A:"Perceptual grouping of sounds based on temporal proximity",B:"The ability to selectively attend to one conversation in a noisy environment while filtering others",C:"Habituation to background noise over time",D:"The phenomenon of hearing one's own name even when not attending to that channel",ans:"B",exp:"The cocktail party effect, studied by Colin Cherry (1953), refers to the ability to focus on a single auditory stimulus (e.g., one conversation) while filtering out other background noise. It demonstrates selective auditory attention. Interestingly, highly salient information — such as hearing one's own name — can break through attentional filters (demonstrating some parallel processing)."},
  {num:66,text:"In problem-solving, a 'functional fixedness' refers to:",A:"The tendency to use the most recent problem-solving strategy regardless of its applicability",B:"The inability to perceive an object being used in a way other than its typical function",C:"The use of algorithms rather than heuristics to solve problems",D:"Overestimating the probability of events that come easily to mind",ans:"B",exp:"Functional fixedness (Duncker, 1945) is a cognitive bias that limits a person to using an object only in the way it is traditionally used. A classic demonstration is the candle problem, where participants fail to use a box of tacks as a platform because they fixate on its conventional use. It is a type of mental set that impedes creative problem-solving."},
  {num:67,text:"Which of the following best describes the 'availability heuristic'?",A:"Making judgements based on how easily examples come to mind",B:"Making decisions based on the most recent information received",C:"Using statistical base rates to estimate probabilities",D:"Judging whether an item belongs to a category based on how closely it matches the prototype",ans:"A",exp:"The availability heuristic (Tversky and Kahneman, 1973) involves estimating the likelihood of an event based on how easily examples come to mind. Because vivid or recent events are recalled more easily, availability can lead to systematic biases — e.g., overestimating the frequency of dramatic deaths (plane crashes) versus mundane ones (heart disease)."},
  {num:68,text:"George Miller's famous paper on working memory capacity suggested that the average span of immediate memory is:",A:"3 ± 1 chunks",B:"5 ± 1 chunks",C:"7 ± 2 chunks",D:"10 ± 2 chunks",ans:"C",exp:"George Miller's landmark 1956 paper 'The Magical Number Seven, Plus or Minus Two' proposed that short-term memory capacity is approximately 7 ± 2 chunks of information. Chunking — organising items into meaningful units — allows more information to be held. More recent research (Cowan, 2001) suggests a capacity closer to 4 chunks."},
  {num:69,text:"Which of the following is an example of a 'top-down' process in perception?",A:"Edge detection by retinal ganglion cells",B:"Detecting luminance contrast",C:"Using prior knowledge and context to interpret an ambiguous image",D:"Processing individual features before recognising the whole object",ans:"C",exp:"Top-down processing refers to the use of prior knowledge, context, expectations, and concepts to guide perception. Reading degraded text using contextual clues, or seeing a face in clouds, are examples. Bottom-up processing, by contrast, builds perception from raw sensory data without prior knowledge. Real-world perception involves both processes simultaneously."},
  {num:70,text:"The phenomenon of 'tip-of-the-tongue' (TOT) state in memory demonstrates:",A:"Complete failure of retrieval from long-term memory",B:"Partial access to stored information — knowing something exists but being unable to fully retrieve it",C:"Interference from recently learned competing information",D:"Failure of the phonological loop in working memory",ans:"B",exp:"The TOT state occurs when a person is confident that information is stored in memory but cannot fully retrieve it, often recalling partial information (e.g., first letter, number of syllables). It demonstrates that retrieval is not all-or-none and that memories have multiple access routes. Brown and McNeill (1966) first studied this phenomenon systematically."},
  {num:71,text:"According to Baddeley's working memory model, the 'phonological loop' is responsible for:",A:"Processing visual and spatial information temporarily",B:"Coordinating and integrating information from other slave systems",C:"Temporarily holding and manipulating verbal and auditory information",D:"Linking working memory to long-term episodic memory",ans:"C",exp:"In Baddeley and Hitch's (1974) Working Memory Model, the phonological loop has two components: the phonological store (briefly holds speech-based information) and the articulatory rehearsal process (refreshes this information by subvocal repetition). It is responsible for processing language-based information and plays a key role in reading and language acquisition."},
  {num:72,text:"The Gestalt principle of 'proximity' in perception states that:",A:"Objects that look similar tend to be grouped together",B:"Objects that are close to each other tend to be perceived as belonging together",C:"Perception tends to complete incomplete figures",D:"People prefer the simplest possible explanation for perceptual patterns",ans:"B",exp:"The Gestalt principle of proximity states that elements close together in space are perceptually grouped as a unit. This is one of several grouping principles (others include similarity, continuity, closure, and common fate) identified by Gestalt psychologists that demonstrate that perception is holistic and organised — 'the whole is greater than the sum of its parts'."},
  {num:73,text:"A researcher finds a correlation of r = -0.85 between daily stress levels and sleep quality. Which of the following is the MOST accurate interpretation?",A:"Higher stress strongly causes poor sleep quality",B:"There is a strong positive relationship between stress and sleep quality",C:"There is a strong negative relationship — as stress increases, sleep quality tends to decrease",D:"The result is statistically insignificant because it is negative",ans:"C",exp:"A correlation of r = -0.85 indicates a strong negative (inverse) relationship: as one variable increases, the other tends to decrease. However, correlation does not imply causation — a third variable or reverse causation may explain the relationship. The negative sign indicates direction; the magnitude (0.85) indicates strength."},
  {num:74,text:"In a between-subjects experimental design, participants are randomly assigned to conditions. What is the PRIMARY advantage of random assignment?",A:"It ensures all participants are similar in age and IQ",B:"It eliminates the possibility of demand characteristics",C:"It controls for individual differences by distributing them equally across conditions",D:"It allows the same participants to be used in all conditions",ans:"C",exp:"Random assignment distributes individual differences (age, personality, intelligence, etc.) approximately equally across experimental conditions, making groups comparable at the outset. This is the key mechanism by which experiments control for confounding variables and allow causal inferences. It does not eliminate individual differences — it distributes them randomly."},
  {num:75,text:"In hypothesis testing, a Type I error refers to:",A:"Failing to reject a false null hypothesis",B:"Rejecting a true null hypothesis (false positive)",C:"Using an overly small sample size",D:"Accepting the alternative hypothesis when it is false",ans:"B",exp:"A Type I error (α) occurs when the null hypothesis is rejected even though it is actually true — a false positive. The probability of a Type I error is set by the significance level (α), typically 0.05. A Type II error (β) is failing to reject a false null hypothesis. Power (1-β) is the probability of correctly detecting a true effect."},
  {num:76,text:"Which of the following non-parametric tests is the equivalent of the independent samples t-test?",A:"Wilcoxon signed-rank test",B:"Kruskal-Wallis test",C:"Mann-Whitney U test",D:"Friedman test",ans:"C",exp:"The Mann-Whitney U test is the non-parametric equivalent of the independent samples t-test, used when data are ordinal or when parametric assumptions (normality, homogeneity of variance) are not met. The Wilcoxon signed-rank test is the non-parametric equivalent of the paired-samples t-test. The Kruskal-Wallis test is the non-parametric equivalent of one-way ANOVA."},
  {num:77,text:"Informed consent in psychological research requires that participants be told:",A:"Only the hypothesis after the study is complete",B:"The true purpose of the study, potential risks, and their right to withdraw, prior to participation",C:"That participation is mandatory and withdrawal is not permitted",D:"Only the general topic area; full disclosure is not required",ans:"B",exp:"Informed consent requires that participants receive sufficient information about the study's purpose, procedures, potential risks and benefits, confidentiality, and their right to withdraw without penalty — before they agree to participate. Exceptions (e.g., deception studies) must be ethically justified and followed by full debriefing."},
  {num:78,text:"Effect size (e.g., Cohen's d) is important in research because it:",A:"Tells the researcher whether to reject the null hypothesis",B:"Indicates the magnitude of the difference or relationship, independent of sample size",C:"Is always higher when statistical significance is achieved",D:"Replaces the need for p-values in all analyses",ans:"B",exp:"Effect size measures the practical or theoretical significance of a finding, independent of sample size. With large enough samples, even trivially small differences become statistically significant (p < 0.05). Cohen's d (for mean differences) and r (for correlations) are common effect size measures. Cohen suggested d = 0.2 (small), 0.5 (medium), 0.8 (large)."},
  {num:79,text:"A study uses naturalistic observation to record children's play behaviour in a school playground without intervening. This is an example of:",A:"A quasi-experimental design",B:"A correlational design",C:"A case study",D:"A non-participant observational method",ans:"D",exp:"Non-participant (or unobtrusive) naturalistic observation involves the researcher observing behaviour in the natural environment without becoming part of the observed group or intervening. It has high ecological validity but low experimental control. Inter-rater reliability is important in ensuring coding of observations is consistent."},
  {num:80,text:"Cronbach's alpha is a measure of:",A:"Test-retest reliability",B:"Inter-rater reliability",C:"Internal consistency reliability",D:"Criterion-related validity",ans:"C",exp:"Cronbach's alpha (α) measures internal consistency — the degree to which all items in a scale measure the same underlying construct. Values range from 0 to 1; generally, α ≥ 0.70 is considered acceptable for research purposes. It is based on the average inter-item correlation and the number of items in the scale."},
  {num:81,text:"The 'fundamental attribution error' (correspondence bias) refers to:",A:"Attributing our own failures to situational factors while attributing others' failures to internal factors",B:"The tendency to overestimate dispositional factors and underestimate situational factors when explaining others' behaviour",C:"The bias toward attributing positive events to our own actions",D:"The tendency to conform to group norms even when we privately disagree",ans:"B",exp:"' behaviour The Fundamental Attribution Error (FAE), described by Lee Ross (1977), is the tendency to overemphasise dispositional (personality) explanations for others' behaviour while underestimating situational influences. For example, attributing a colleague's tardiness to laziness rather than traffic. The actor-observer bias extends this: we apply situational attributions to our own behaviour."},
  {num:82,text:"Stanley Milgram's obedience experiments demonstrated that:",A:"Only sadistic or aggressive individuals would administer dangerous shocks",B:"A significant majority of ordinary people would administer apparently lethal shocks when instructed by an authority figure",C:"Obedience is entirely determined by personality traits",D:"Physical proximity of the authority figure had no effect on compliance rates",ans:"B",exp:"Milgram's (1963) studies showed that approximately 65% of participants administered what they believed to be maximum (450V, 'XXX') shocks to a confederate when instructed by an experimenter. This demonstrated that situational factors — authority, legitimacy, proximity — can override personal values and cause ordinary people to engage in harmful obedience."},
  {num:83,text:"The 'bystander effect' (diffusion of responsibility) refers to the phenomenon where:",A:"People are more likely to help when they are alone than when others are present",B:"People always help in emergencies regardless of group size",C:"The presence of multiple bystanders increases the probability of intervention",D:"Bystanders invariably contact emergency services in a crisis",ans:"A",exp:"The bystander effect, investigated by Latané and Darley after the Kitty Genovese case, shows that individuals are less likely to offer help in an emergency when others are present. This is due to diffusion of responsibility (each person assumes someone else will act) and pluralistic ignorance (each bystander looks to others for cues and interprets inaction as normalcy)."},
  {num:84,text:"Henri Tajfel's Social Identity Theory proposes that in-group favouritism arises because:",A:"In-groups have objective material advantages over out-groups",B:"People derive self-esteem partly from their group memberships and are motivated to see their group positively",C:"Competition for scarce resources inevitably creates inter-group conflict",D:"People are genetically programmed to prefer those who are similar to them",ans:"B",exp:"Social Identity Theory (Tajfel and Turner, 1979) proposes that people derive part of their self-concept from the social groups they belong to (social identity). To maintain positive self-esteem, they are motivated to perceive their in-group as superior to out-groups (in-group favouritism). Minimal group paradigm studies showed this occurs even with arbitrary, meaningless group assignments."},
  {num:85,text:"Cognitive dissonance, a concept central to Leon Festinger's theory, MOST commonly motivates people to:",A:"Seek out information that confirms their existing attitudes",B:"Tolerate inconsistencies and accept uncertainty",C:"Reduce psychological discomfort by changing attitudes, behaviours, or adding cognitions",D:"Become more rigid in their existing beliefs",ans:"C",exp:"Cognitive dissonance (Festinger, 1957) arises when a person holds inconsistent beliefs or behaviours. This creates psychological discomfort, motivating the person to restore consistency by: (1) changing one of the conflicting beliefs, (2) acquiring new cognitions to justify the inconsistency, or (3) reducing the importance of the dissonant cognition."},
  {num:86,text:"The 'just-world hypothesis' proposed by Melvin Lerner suggests that people:",A:"Act justly because they fear social punishment",B:"Believe the world is fundamentally fair and that people get what they deserve",C:"Perceive injustice as normal and inevitable",D:"Prefer an uncertain world to a predictable one",ans:"B",exp:"Melvin Lerner's (1980) Just-World Hypothesis proposes that people have a strong need to believe the world is a fair and orderly place where people get what they deserve. This belief helps maintain a sense of safety and control. However, it can lead to blaming victims (e.g., rape victims, the poor) for their misfortune to preserve the belief in a just world."},
  {num:87,text:"The phenomenon of 'social loafing' refers to:",A:"Conforming to group norms even when privately disagreeing",B:"The tendency for individuals to exert less effort in group tasks than when working alone",C:"Adopting the behaviour of strangers in ambiguous situations",D:"The increased motivation and performance when being observed",ans:"B",exp:"Social loafing (Latané et al., 1979) is the tendency for individuals to reduce effort when working collectively on a shared task compared to working individually. It occurs because individual contributions are less identifiable and individual responsibility is diffused. It is reduced when individual contributions are identifiable and tasks are personally meaningful."},
  {num:88,text:"Philip Zimbardo's Stanford Prison Experiment (1971) is most often cited as evidence for:",A:"The genetic basis of aggressive and authoritarian behaviour",B:"The power of situational roles and contexts in shaping behaviour",C:"The effectiveness of prison as a rehabilitative institution",D:"Dispositional factors being more important than situational factors",ans:"B",exp:"Zimbardo's study, in which students were randomly assigned as 'guards' or 'prisoners' in a simulated prison, demonstrated how quickly situational roles can lead to dramatic changes in behaviour. Guards became increasingly authoritarian and abusive; prisoners became passive and distressed. The study was halted after 6 days and highlighted the power of social roles and situations."},
  {num:89,text:"The Big Five personality model (OCEAN) includes which of the following dimensions?",A:"Openness, Conscientiousness, Extraversion, Agreeableness, Neuroticism",B:"Openness, Confidence, Extraversion, Awareness, Neuroticism",C:"Organisation, Creativity, Empathy, Agreeableness, Neuroticism",D:"Optimism, Conscientiousness, Extraversion, Assertiveness, Negativity",ans:"A",exp:"The Big Five (OCEAN) model identifies five broad personality dimensions: Openness to Experience, Conscientiousness, Extraversion, Agreeableness, and Neuroticism (emotional instability). It is one of the most empirically robust models in personality psychology, supported across cultures and ages, and strongly associated with various life outcomes."},
  {num:90,text:"In Freudian theory, the defence mechanism of 'reaction formation' involves:",A:"Channelling unacceptable impulses into socially acceptable activities",B:"Expressing the opposite of what one truly feels to reduce anxiety",C:"Attributing one's own unacceptable qualities to others",D:"Reverting to an earlier stage of development under stress",ans:"B",exp:"Reaction formation is a psychoanalytic defence mechanism in which an individual expresses attitudes or behaviours that are the direct opposite of their true feelings, which are anxiety-provoking. For example, someone with unconscious hostile feelings toward a parent may display exaggerated affection. It involves converting an unacceptable impulse into its opposite."},
  {num:91,text:"Alfred Adler's concept of the 'inferiority complex' refers to:",A:"A neurological deficit affecting cognitive processing",B:"A conscious awareness of being inferior to others in intelligence",C:"An exaggerated, pervasive sense of personal inadequacy that interferes with healthy development",D:"The mechanism by which the ego defends against superego demands",ans:"C",exp:"Alfred Adler proposed that all individuals are motivated by an inferiority complex — feelings of inadequacy that arise in childhood when we realise our smallness and dependence. Healthy individuals compensate through striving for superiority (mastery). An inferiority complex occurs when these feelings are overwhelming, leading to overcompensation (e.g., arrogance, bullying) or retreat."},
  {num:92,text:"Carl Rogers' theory of personality emphasised the importance of:",A:"Libidinal energy, oral and anal stages, and the unconscious",B:"Archetypes, the collective unconscious, and individuation",C:"The self-concept, the ideal self, and the drive toward self-actualisation",D:"Organ inferiority, birth order, and social interest",ans:"C",exp:"Carl Rogers proposed a humanistic theory of personality centred on the self-concept (one's perceptions and evaluations of oneself), the ideal self (who one wants to be), and self-actualisation (the drive toward realising one's full potential). Psychological maladjustment arises when there is a large incongruence between the self-concept and experience."},
  {num:93,text:"Which of the following is classified as a mature ego defence mechanism by George Vaillant?",A:"Splitting",B:"Denial",C:"Sublimation",D:"Regression",ans:"C",exp:"George Vaillant's hierarchical model classifies defence mechanisms from immature to mature. Mature defences include sublimation (channelling unacceptable impulses into socially valued activities), humour, suppression, and altruism. Denial and regression are neurotic/immature. Splitting is a primitive/immature defence associated with BPD."},
  {num:94,text:"Erik Erikson described 'generativity vs. stagnation' as the psychosocial crisis of:",A:"Late adolescence (18–25 years)",B:"Early adulthood (20s–30s)",C:"Middle adulthood (40s–60s)",D:"Late adulthood (60+ years)",ans:"C",exp:"Erikson's stage of Generativity vs. Stagnation occurs in middle adulthood (approximately 40–65 years). Generativity involves contributing to society — through raising children, mentoring, or creative/productive work. Success leads to the virtue of care; failure results in stagnation — a sense of self-absorption and lack of meaningful contribution."},
  {num:95,text:"The Mental Health Care Act (MHCA) 2017 in India specifically states that every person has the right to:",A:"Be hospitalised involuntarily at a family member's request without consent",B:"Make an advance directive about mental health treatment",C:"Be tried in a special court for offences related to mental illness",D:"Receive treatment exclusively from government facilities",ans:"B",exp:"The Mental Health Care Act 2017 (India) grants individuals the right to make advance directives — documents specifying how they wish to be treated (or not treated) for mental illness in the event they lose capacity to consent in the future. The Act represents a rights-based approach to mental health care and aligns with the UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities (CRPD)."},
  {num:96,text:"The M'Naghten Rules (1843) in forensic psychology address the legal standard for:",A:"Fitness to stand trial and competency",B:"The insanity defence — grounds for not holding a person criminally responsible",C:"Sentencing guidelines for mentally ill offenders",D:"Involuntary psychiatric hospitalisation",ans:"B",exp:"The M'Naghten Rules, arising from the trial of Daniel M'Naghten (1843), established the legal standard for the insanity defence in English-speaking jurisdictions. A defendant may be acquitted if, at the time of the act, they were suffering from a mental disease such that they did not know the nature of the act, or did not know that what they were doing was wrong."},
  {num:97,text:"Malingering in a forensic context refers to:",A:"Genuine psychiatric illness that impairs a defendant's ability to stand trial",B:"The intentional feigning or exaggeration of symptoms for external gain (e.g., avoiding prosecution, obtaining compensation)",C:"A dissociative state following trauma in which criminal acts are committed without awareness",D:"An involuntary misrepresentation of symptoms due to somatic symptom disorder",ans:"B",exp:"Malingering (DSM-5 Z76.5) involves the intentional production of false or grossly exaggerated physical or psychological symptoms, motivated by external incentives such as avoiding military service, criminal prosecution, or obtaining financial compensation. It is distinguished from factitious disorder (internal motivation — adopting the sick role) and conversion disorder (unconscious symptom production)."},
  {num:98,text:"The Rehabilitation Council of India (RCI) Act was enacted in which year?",A:"1986",B:"1990",C:"1992",D:"2000",ans:"C",exp:"The Rehabilitation Council of India Act was enacted in 1992. The RCI is a statutory body under the Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment that regulates and monitors training policies and programmes in the field of rehabilitation and special education. It maintains a Central Rehabilitation Register of qualified professionals."},
  {num:99,text:"The Rights of Persons with Disabilities Act (RPwD) 2016 in India recognises how many specified disabilities?",A:"7",B:"14",C:"21",D:"28",ans:"C",exp:"The Rights of Persons with Disabilities (RPwD) Act 2016 replaced the earlier Persons with Disabilities Act 1995 and expanded the number of recognised disabilities from 7 to 21. These include physical, sensory, intellectual, and mental health conditions. The Act guarantees equality of opportunity, non-discrimination, and rights to education, employment, and social protection."},
  {num:100,text:"In research ethics, the principle of 'beneficence' requires that researchers:",A:"Obtain voluntary, informed consent from all participants",B:"Treat all participants with equal respect regardless of group membership",C:"Maximise potential benefits of the research and minimise potential harms",D:"Maintain confidentiality of all data collected",ans:"C",exp:"The principle of beneficence, drawn from the Belmont Report (1979), requires researchers to maximise potential benefits and minimise potential harms to participants. It is paired with non-maleficence (do no harm). Together with respect for autonomy (informed consent) and justice (fair selection of participants), beneficence forms the ethical foundation of research involving human subjects. — End of Answer Key —"}
];
